<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Czechoslovakia-Ecology     02-11 0148</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Czechoslovakia-Ecology,0151</SECOND>
<HEAD>Entire National Park Polluted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Giant Mountains National Park,
Czechoslovakia's largest, has become so heavily polluted that half
its trees are severely damaged, the Communist Party daily Rude Pravo
reported.
   It said Friday that the 80,000-acre park, a popular skiing resort
80 miles north of Prague, has been damaged by pollution from
chemical plants and power stations using low-grade coal.
   ``Over 5O percent of pollution comes from the equipment of our
neighbors,'' Rude Pravo quoted Vladimir Korinek of the Forests and
Water Ministry as saying. He apparently was referring to factories
in nearby Poland and East Germany.
   The paper quoted Korinek as saying the fate of two ski-jumping
hills in Harrachov, a prime venue for international competitions,
would likely be affected by ecological disaster _ ``There are no
trees left and there is simply too much wind, which makes
ski-jumping dangerous.''
</TEXT>
