<DOCNO> AP890211-0011 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-11-89 0144EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-AntiquarianFair     02-11 0560</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Antiquarian Fair,0576</SECOND>
<HEAD>Antiquarian Fair Lures Longtime Buyers, Ensnares New Devotees</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: First available for Saturday AMs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATALINA ORTIZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The aroma of old leather mingled with the
smell of new money at the nation's largest book fair, where you
could pick up a 1632 edition of Shakespeare or ``The Philosophy of
Andy Warhol'' bound with $5 bills.
   ``I love to lose myself in other men's minds,'' wrote Charles
Lamb in an essay on books and reading, and he would have been
blissfully transported at the California International Antiquarian
Book Fair, which opened Friday.
   Organizers hoped a record 8,000 people would browse through the
centuries of writers' and bookbinders' art, not to mention buy.
   But the 188 booksellers from throughout the United States and
seven other countries anticipated winning new devotees as well as
making profits.
   ``Book fairs cultivate book collectors. They come here and see
things they've never seen before,'' said George Robert Kane, a
bookseller and chairman of this year's fair.
   ``They love literature or see the beauty of the illustrations.
... They get into it, and pretty soon, they're hooked,'' said Kane,
whose necktie was printed with rows of books.
   ``In most cases, it's a consuming disease _ a consuming passion,
that's better.''
   Future collectors might catch the bug while admiring a second
folio edition of Shakespeare's plays, offered for $60,000, a
painstakingly illuminated 15th century Flemmish manuscript Book of
Hours for $35,000 or a 1482 Venetian volume of Euclid priced at
$25,000.
   The most expensive item is a three-volume set of the first
edition of Moby Dick, published in England in 1851 and entitled The
Whale. It's price? A quick $75,000. But it's in first-class
condition and a gold-embossed whale adorns the spine of each volume.
   Collectors on a tighter budget could choose an autographed copy
of Oscar Wilde's ``An Ideal Husband'' bound in gold-stamped blue
morocco leather and costing $4,950.
   Even some 20th century authors command a handsome price. A first
edition of Ian Fleming's ``Casino Royale,'' for example, is offered
for $1,250.
   Despite fears that television and videos have produced a nation
of people who don't read, dealers said growing numbers of people are
becoming fascinated by _ and buying _ rare books.
   ``Business is better that it's ever been,'' said Jerry Weinstein,
manager of Heritage Book Shop Inc. in Los Angeles.
   Some collectors think of their purchases as investments that will
increase in value with the years. But even collectors with an eye
toward possible resale buy the old and rare volumnes primarily out
of love.
   ``The preponderance of them are buying not for investment but for
just having it as something beautiful, just like having a Picasso,''
Weinstein said.
   Having something rare and beautiful doesn't have to cost
thousands of dollars. Prices at the fair start at about $20, and
some first editions of well-known authors such as John Steinbeck and
F. Scott Fitzgerald can be had for about $100.
   ``If you fall in love with an illustrator or an author ... from
Elior Wylie to Shakespeare ... you'll search for the things you can
afford,'' said Kane, who gave up newspaper work to become a book
dealer in Santa Cruz 18 years ago.
   A part of the admission proceeds from the fair, which continues
through Sunday, goes to the San Francisco Public Library.
</TEXT>
