<FIRST>r w PM-RailMX     02-11 0562</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rail MX,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Air Force Says Environmental Impact Minimal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Air Force study concludes that deploying
huge MX nuclear missiles on railroad cars would neither interfere
with the operation of the nation's rail network nor harm the
environment significantly.
   The final Environmental Impact Statement, released Friday at the
Pentagon, turned up some problems at a few of the 11 Air Force bases
that are being considered as candidates for ``rail garrisons.''
   But the statement insists that ``while there is a very slight
potential for accidents with the deployment of the (MX) Rail
Garrison System, the system would be safe and would pose negligible
risk to human health and the environment.''
   Former President Reagan ordered the development of a rail-basing
plan for the 10-warhead MX _ a weapon he dubbed the Peacekeeper _ in
December 1986. His goal was to overcome congressional concerns about
the vulnerability of the missiles inside underground silos.
   President Bush is now facing a March 15 congressional deadline to
decide if he'll back Reagan's plan. If he does, and Congress agrees,
the Air Force plans to build 25 six-car trains with each carrying
two MX missiles. Each garrison could house up to four trains.
   Because of the small number of trains involved, the conclusion
Friday that the system would not interfere with commercial
operations had been expected. The Air Force also went out of its way
to note that training operations for crews would be conducted with
fake trains that wouldn't carry real MX missiles.
   In the event of a derailment or other accident, the chances of an
explosion or fire involving the missile's propellants are
``unlikely'' and for the nuclear warheads, virtually impossible, the
report says.
   ``U.S. nuclear weapons include safety features and control over
arming mechanisms that assure there is virtually no possibility of
an inadvertent nuclear detonation,'' the report states.
   The rail car launchers would remain inside fortified military
bases unless there was a threat of war, and only then would scramble
on the commercial rail network to avoid a Soviet first-strike
attack, the Air Force said.
   The heaviest environmental impact would stem from construction
activities at any bases selected to serve as garrisons for the MX
cars, the Air Force said. Those would consist primarily of increased
traffic congestion, the short-term degradation of air quality and in
a few instances, the relocation of inhabited buildings.
   Of the 11 Air Force bases reviewed, however, four would likely
suffer ``significant degradation of biological resources'' if rail
garrisons were built, the Air Force reported.
   Those four are Barksdale Air Force Base, La.; Fairchild Air Force
Base, Wash.; Whiteman Air Force Base, Mo.; and Wurtsmith Air Force
Base, Mich.
   Despite those findings, the impact statement offers no ranking of
the 11 bases, nor does it disqualify any base from consideration.
   It repeats a decision made two years ago that F.E. Warren Air
Force Base, Wyo., will be the headquarters and first home for any MX
trains. But it noted that rail deployment has not been approved by
Congress and that it is premature to select other bases.
   The other bases considered candidates are Eaker Air Force Base
and Little Rock Air Force Base in Arkansas; Dyess Air Force Base,
Texas; Grand Forks Air Force Base and Minot Air Force Base in North
Dakota; and Malstrom Air Force Base, Mont.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890211-0013 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-11-89 0148EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-TradeZones     02-11 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Trade Zones,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study Says Trade-Zone Program Hurts US Parts Makers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressional study concludes that a
foreign-trade zone program intended to encourage U.S. exports
instead is helping foreign auto parts manufacturers by giving
millions of dollars in tariff breaks.
   ``Although originally created in order to encourage
export-oriented trade, in its current form the program provides
greater benefits to firms who import more parts,'' the General
Accounting Office, the investigative arm of Congress, said in a
report issued Friday.
   The report was immediately praised by the Automotive Parts and
Accessories Association.
   The GAO's findings ``underscore our industry's conviction that
the ... program is broken and needs fixing,'' said the trade
association's president, Julian Morris, from its Lanham, Md.,
headquarters.
   The report recommended that Congress amend the 1934 foreign-trade
zone law to provide guidance on what public benefits are needed to
justify such zones or subzones. Factors to be considered would be
exports, imports, employment and investment.
   Foreign trade zones were originally created to encourage the
export of U.S. goods that contain foreign parts. The program,
however, has ``become a major base'' for manufacturers serving
domestic markets, the report said.
   The GAO report, requested in 1987 by Rep. Dan Rostenkowski,
D-Ill. and chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee, estimated
the foreign-trade zones and their subzones in 1986 reduced tariffs
on auto parts by $38 million.
   The value of parts flowing through the subzones has risen
explosively, from $200 million in 1978 to $5 billion in 1986, the
report said.
   Rep. Sander Levin, D-Mich. a member of the House Ways and Means
Committee, said the discrepancy between tariffs on parts and on
finished vehicles created an obvious ``private benefit'' for
automakers under the program.
   Imported auto parts are subject to tariffs ranging from 4 percent
to 11 percent. Finished vehicles are assessed at a 2.5 percent
tariff rate.
   When vehicles built in foreign-trade zones are sold in the United
States, the imported parts are taxed at the lower 2.5 percent rate,
Levin said.
   Automakers using the foreign-trade zone program run the spectrum
from the Michigan-based domestic giants _ General Motors Corp., Ford
Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. _ to foreign makers like Nissan, Toyota
and Mazda that have established assembly plants in the United States.
   Most auto assembly plants in the United States come under the
program, the GAO said.
   Although the Foreign Trade Zone Board, which administers the
program, uses public benefit as its criterion for judging requests,
that standard has not been officially adopted and applications have
seldom been denied, the report said.
   The report recommended the public benefit standard be made part
of the law.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
