<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Jews     02-11 0691</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Jews,0710</SECOND>
<HEAD>World Jewish Leaders to Open First Soviet Jewish Center in 50 Years</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: First available for Saturday AMs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nobel laureate Elie Wiesel and dozens of other
world Jewish leaders are coming to Moscow to help open the first
cultural center for Soviet Jews in more than 50 years.
   While one of the leaders hailed Sunday's opening of the center as
a sign of the improving fortunes of the country's 1.8 million Jews
under President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, he said it's too soon to
declare an end to the problems of Jews in the Soviet Union.
   ``Glasnost has taken hold here. The question will be, can it
continue?'' said Rabbi Marvin Hier, dean of the Simon Wiesenthal
Center in Los Angeles.
   Hier, World Jewish Congress President Edgar Bronfman, and Wiesel
_ a survivor of the Holocaust and 1986 Nobel Peace Prize winner _
are to speak at Sunday's opening of the Solomon Mikhoels Cultural
Center. About 70 Jewish leaders from Israel, Britain, France,
Australia, Canada, the United States and other countries plan to
attend.
   The opening comes a few days after a Soviet newspaper made a
major admission: that Soviet Jews have suffered discrimination for
decades and that dictator Josef Stalin destroyed Jewish culture in
the country.
   Mikhoels, a Jewish actor for whom the center was named, was among
the thousands of Jews who fell victim to Stalin's terror. He was
killed in 1948 in what was officially termed a traffic accident but
what many Jews believe was an assassination ordered by Stalin.
   The center is located in the Moscow Jewish Musical Theater on
Taganka Square in the southeastern section of the capital.
   Its director, Mikhail Gluz, told the official news agency Tass on
Friday that Yiddish and Hebrew classes are planned, itself a major
change. The teaching of Hebrew was once punished as a crime, and
several Jewish activists were jailed for religious instruction.
   Soviet laws bar the private teaching of religious subjects to
anyone under 18, but authorities have indicated a new law on
religion being drafted will ease those and other restrictions.
   Hier said in an interview that Soviet promises to allow the
teaching of Hebrew as well as membership by Soviet Jews in
international Jewish organizations ``have been couched in very
diplomatic terms.''
   ``We have no commitment yet,'' he said.
   In a report previewing Sunday's opening, Tass said: ``The
perestroika, or restructuring drive, has altered the life of Soviet
society and prompted the development of Jewish cultural
associations.''
   But Hier said plans for the center to have a public library,
Jewish museum and art gallery could be ruined if Soviet authorities
interfere.
   ``It is not the time to be euphoric, but to make sure the center
will be free to develop cultural and educational programs. If that
is what the center becomes, it will be a great and epic event,''
Hier said.
   If authorities step in, he said, ``we will be back where we
started from.''
   The Simon Wiesenthal Center has donated to the center an exhibit
and Russian-language books about the Nazi campaign against the Jews,
and has shown in Moscow a film that accuses the Soviet Union of
kidnapping Raoul Wallenberg, a Swedish diplomat who saved thousands
of Jews during World War II and later disappeared.
   As part of his effort to improve relations with the West,
Gorbachev has taken several steps to address complaints that his
country violates human rights.
   For Jews, the changes have meant a rise in emigration _ 1988
marked an eight-year high with about 20,000 leaving _ less
harassment at Jewish holiday celebrations, and the opening of a
private Jewish museum and library in Moscow.
   But Mikhail Chlenov, a member of a private group called the
Jewish Cultural Association, said the government has a long way to
go.
   ``Jewish life in the U.S.S.R. is in a state of crisis,'' he wrote
in a brochure on the Mikhoels center. ``Official Jewish cultural
institutions ... such as magazines, newspapers and theaters do not
satisfy the demands of our time. The growing Jewish consciousness
refuses to be compressed into an outlived framework.''
</TEXT>
