<FIRST>r w PM-Budget     02-11 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Budget,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressional Democrats Say Bush Budget is a Trap for Them</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic chairmen of the House and Senate
budget committees meet with White House budget officials next week
to try to find out what they say President Bush's 1990 budget
neglected to reveal: how the deficit will be trimmed.
   House Budget Committee Chairman Leon Panetta, D-Calif., and his
Senate counterpart, Jim Sasser, D-Tenn., said Friday they would not
proceed with the high-level budget negotiations the Bush
administration wants until they get those details on deficit
reduction.
   ``Before we go any further, we want to sit down and find out
specifically where they're going, program by program,'' Sasser said.
   The lawmakers said Bush's $1.16 trillion spending plan was vague
when it came to specifying savings, a strategy aimed at putting the
pressure _ and the blame _ on Congress for cuts that will inevitably
be unpopular.
   ``Mr. Bush chose to give us only the good news,'' Panetta said of
the president's budget address Thursday night to Congress. ``He has
left it for Congress to give the American people the bad news.''
   Bush said his proposal would leave a deficit of $91.1 billion
next year, well within the $100 billion target required by the
Gramm-Rudman deficit reduction law.
   He achieves that level by holding the growth in the defense
budget to the rate of inflation, providing $309 billion in new
spending; making a controversial cut in the capital gains tax rate
that he says will raise $4.8 billion in new revenues; slowing the
growth of Medicare by $5 billion; selling $3.7 billion in federal
assets; and extending taxes on telephone service and airline tickets
that are due to expire.
   But of most concern to Democrats is Bush's proposal to limit a
collection of more than 1,000 programs _ most of them domestic _ to
the $136 billion spent for them this year. Democrats said this meant
that Bush was leaving the onus for finding $11 billion in cuts up to
them, reductions that could affect programs like toxic waste
cleanups, mass transit assistance, and law enforcement.
   ``This is not what we would call a flexible freeze,'' Panetta
said, referring to Bush's campaign promise to reduce the deficit by
limiting spending increases to the rate of inflation. ``It's a
flexible squeeze.''
   Sen. Pete Domenici of New Mexico, the ranking Republican on the
Senate Budget Committee, defended Bush's strategy of lumping those
programs together.
   ``There's more room for negotiation this way,'' he said.
   Darman briefed Republican senators and representatives on the
budget early Friday, and told reporters afterward that it is time
for the administration and congressional leaders to begin
negotiating on a spending plan.
   ``The spirit is very good at the moment and we've got to build on
that spirit,'' he said.
</TEXT>
