<FIRST>u a AM-PlaneFire     02-11 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Plane Fire,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>Air National Guard Plane Crashes, Crew Member Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WAYNE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A military aircraft crashed Friday night
despite efforts of a crew member to land the plane when the cockpit
caught fire and the pilot lost consciousness. One crew member was
killed, officials said.
   The weapons specialist aboard the F-4 Air National Guard plane
tried to land the craft but bailed out before it crashed on a runway
at the city airport, said supervisor Larry Schneider at Baer Field's
control tower.
   Lt. Kathleen Rzepka of the Indiana Air National Guard said one
crew member was killed and the other was hospitalized. She did not
know his condition. It was not immediately known which of the two on
board died.
   Earlier, patrolman Ed Bradley said the pilot was in very critical
condition, according to medics at the scene. He did not believe the
weapons specialist had suffered serious injuries.
   Both men were taken to Lutheran Hospital, but a nursing
supervisor there said no information would be released pending
notification of relatives.
   Police learned about the pilotless plane, when the craft was six
minutes away from Baer Field, Bradley said.
   The weapons specialist piloted the plane to the runway, but
ejected before it landed. There was no fire at the scene of the
crash and the fire in the cockpit had been extinguished, Bradley
said.
   Capt. Gregg Dickerson, squadron flight surgeon for the Indiana
Air National Guard, said an Air Force accident board would be
appointed to investigate the crash.
