<FILEID>AP-NR-02-11-89 0206EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FairnessDoctrine     02-11 0534</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fairness Doctrine,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Doctrine Supporters Hope for New Legislation in Wake of Ruling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supporters of laws to force broadcasters to
present both sides of controversial issues say they're heartened by
the refusal of a federal appeals court to consider the
constitutionality of such a statute.
   The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia
ruled Friday that the Federal Communications Commission properly
used its authority in August 1987 when it repealed the so-called
Fairness Doctrine.
   The commission had said the doctrine, written in 1949, no longer
served the public interest as defined by the 1934 Communications Act
and was unconstitutional on First Amendment grounds.
   The appeals court said the FCC was ``exercising both its
congressionally delegated power and its expertise'' when it said the
law did not serve the public interest.
   But the court sidestepped the constitutionality question, which
had been a primary issue in the court challenge. The doctrine's
constitutionality is likely to be tested if Congress writes the
doctrine into law again this year as expected.
   ``The big victory here is that any law that Congress passes ...
will not be presumptively unconstitutional,'' said Gigi B. Sohn, an
attorney representing an anti-nuclear group whose fairness complaint
against a Syracuse, N.Y., television station led to the FCC's repeal
of the doctrine.
   The court's decision ``leaves the door wide open for
congressional action to codify the Fairness Doctrine,'' said John H.
Buchanan, chairman of People for the American Way, a constitutional
liberties group.
   Rep. Edward J. Markey, D-Mass., whose Energy and Commerce
telecommunications subcommittee held hearings on a new fairness bill
Thursday, also said the court's decision gave Congress the green
light to pass the measure.
   ``I pledge that the FCC's ill-considered decision to repeal the
Fairness Doctrine will be remedied at expeditiously as possible,''
Markey said.
   The FCC, however, said the court ``has vindicated the public's
right to receive broadcast press coverage free from government
interference.''
   President Bush has said he would veto a Fairness Doctrine bill.
Proponents have said they expect a First Amendment test in the
Supreme Court.
   All three judges concurred in Friday's ruling, although there
were partial dissents.
   In its complaint to the FCC, the anti-nuclear Syracuse Peace
Council said that WTVH, a Meredith Corp. station, had not presented
conflicting views when the station ran a series of advertisements in
1982 that said the Nine Mile 2 nuclear power plant was a ``sound
investment for New York.''
   The FCC agreed with the anti-nuclear group, and Meredith appealed
to the FCC in 1985 on grounds the Fairness Doctrine violated its
First Amendment rights. But the FCC denied the petition, saying the
constitutional question should be left in the hands of Congress and
the courts.
   However, in January 1987 the federal appeals court in Washington
ordered the FCC to consider the constitutional challenge.
   Congress stepped in and wrote the doctrine into law, but
President Reagan vetoed the bill in June 1987 before the FCC
repealed the doctrine.
   Writing for the court Friday, Judge Stephen F. Williams said
``The FCC's decision that the Fairness Doctrine no longer served the
public interest was neither arbitrary, capricious nor an abuse of
discretion.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890211-0019 </DOCNO>
