<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Sweden-Seals     02-11 0126</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Sweden-Seals,0128</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mild Winter Threatens Seal Population</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SODERHAMN, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gray seals, thinned out by past hunting
and chemical pollution, face a new threat this spring because warm
temperatures have melted away their calving areas on the Baltic ice.
   The national news agency TT reported Friday that 100 seals had
gathered near Soderhamn along the central Baltic Sea coast,
apparently in search of the ice floes where they usually bear their
young.
   Most of the Baltic is ice-free, and Sweden is more than halfway
through the mildest winter in recorded history.
   An estimated 1,500 gray seals remain in the Baltic. The seals
numbered about 100,000 in 1900, but were hunted through most of this
century because they compete with commercial fishermen for their
catch.
</TEXT>
