<SECOND>PM-Quayle,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quayle Addresses Human Rights in Domestic Appearances</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dan Quayle, in his first domestic trip as vice
president, gave a pair of speeches on human rights and democracy,
singling out Cuba, Nicaragua, Israel and El Salvador as needing
improvement.
   In remarks to the Cuban American Bar Association on Friday night,
the vice president attacked Fidel Castro's Cuba as ``an obstacle to
democracy and human rights for the Cuban people and people
throughout the region.''
   ``It is a country that has compiled a record of brutality and
oppression that is without parallel in the history of our
hemisphere. And it is a country whose leader has come to personify
they tyranny that the rest of Latin America is trying to cast off
once and for all.''
   Similarly, Quayle attacked Nicaragua, accusing the Sandinista
government of driving its citizens into exile through repression of
freedom, thus causing the massive influx of refugees into Florida.
   He said the Bush administration currently backs the diplomatic
efforts ongoing in Central America in lieu of military aid to the
Contra rebels, but added, ``We will not yield in our determination
to end Nicaragua's threat to democracy in Central America.''
   Quayle said the U.S.-backed government in El Salvador also must
do better on human rights.
   Mentioning his trip to El Salvador last Friday, in which he
warned the government and military that their sizable U.S. aid might
be jeopardized if the country's human rights record did not improve,
Quayle told the Cuban-American group, ``I believe I succeeded in
getting my message across.''
   While State Department statistics show that political murders
have declined from a high of 750 per month there in 1980 to 18 per
month in 1988, Quayle said that figure `is still unacceptable.''
   But Quayle blamed the worst human rights abuses in El Salvador on
the leftist guerrillas trying to overthrow the democratic government.
   Earlier in a speech to the Anti-Defamation League of B'nai
B'rith, Quayle reinforced the recent State Department report that
faulted Israel's armed forces for excessive measures against
Palestinian civilians.
   Quayle said the number of civilian deaths in the Israeli-occupied
Gaza Strip and West Bank were ``clearly unacceptable.''
   Still, the vice president promised, the Bush administration wants
to strengthen longstanding and close U.S.-Israeli ties.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
