<FIRST>r a PM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0405 02-11 0707</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0405,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Delays Action on Pay Raise</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 11th graf pvs, bgng Maintained there, to CORRECT rate to
point; picks up 12th graf, ``I would xxx; Prenoon lede unlikely.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush says he's putting the
volatile issue of congressional pay raises on the back burner,
delaying any new move until ``the timing is right.''
   Chatting with reporters en route to this seacoast resort from a
summit in Ottawa with Canadian Prime Minister Brian Mulroney, Bush
said there had been ``a lot of wounds, a lot of hemorrhaging'' on
Capitol Hill over the pay raises.
   The president said that while he signed House and Senate
legislation rejecting a 51 percent pay raise, he still believes in a
substantial increase for Congress, the federal judiciary and top
government executives.
   Closing out the third full week of his presidency, Bush on Friday:
   _Gave Mulroney personal assurances that he would move as quickly
as possible to attack the acid rain pollution problem in the United
States, which also has harmed Canada's environment.
   But the president gave the Canadian prime minister no precise
timetables for reducing sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxide emissions
from coal-burning plants, mostly in the industrial Midwest.
   Bush said he believed Mulroney was ``reasonably well satisfied''
with his statements on the issue.
   _Said he had not talked to Secretary of State James A. Baker III
about reports that Baker faces a potential conflict-of-interest
problem.
   ``I know there is nobody more ethical than Jim Baker,'' Bush told
reporters aboard Air Force One as he headed to his family compound
for a weekend of relaxation.
   Baker told reporters in Ottawa he is seeking a waiver from
ethical requirements so he could continue to hold stock in Chemical
New York Corp., a bank holding company that has lent some $4.5
billion to Third World countries.
   _Maintained there is no inflation scare in the United States,
despite fresh producer price figures showing a full percentage point
increase during January. This translated into an annual inflation
rate of 12.7 percent.
   ``I would not make assumptions based on one monthly release,''
Bush said. ``And I am not overly concerned about inflation at this
point.'' He did say, however, that ``I don't like the figures.''
   _Said that ``I'm very pleased'' with congressional reaction to
the $1.16 trillion fiscal 1990 budget he proposed to a joint session
of the House and Senate.
   Bush acknowledged his plan did not go into detail on what areas
of spending should be cut, saying ``there's a big black hole in the
budget.''
   But he also said that ``I did what I said I'd do: Here's what I
want to do.'' He said he was ``certainly conscious of the fact''
that there would be arguments with lawmakers over spending
priorities.
   Bush planned a relatively quiet weekend with his wife, Barbara,
and other family members. He said he likely would go to church
Sunday, and hinted that he might go out jogging, saying that he had
been unable to get enough exercise recently because he suffered from
a cold.
   On the lingering question of pay raises for Congress, judges and
senior executives, Bush retreated somewhat from his statement of
last Wednesday, when he suggested he would propose a new pay package
in the wake of the congressional defeat of the 51 percent raise.
   ``All I can do is make recommendations to the Congress about the
future legislation,'' he said. But he said that ``I don't want to do
something that'll look like I am simply trying to step into the
breach and raise a problem that already has caused a great deal of
divisiveness in the Capitol.''
   ``That's not what I want to do,'' he said. ``I've got to rely on
my people here to make a recommendation to me when I can be
effective for the changes that I think are overdue,'' Bush said.
   ``But what you don't want to do is come in and, when the wounded
are still lying on the battlefield, and start fighting another
battle,'' he said. ``Let's take a little time. ... I'm not sure the
timing is right. I think we've got to let the dust settle over that
battlefield.''
</TEXT>
