<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Department Charges Operator of Fitness Centers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The operator of Holiday Spa fitness centers in
six states was accused by the Justice Department of discriminating
against blacks who seek membership in the exercise clubs.
   In a civil suit filed in U.S. District Court here on Friday, the
department charged that U.S. Health Inc. had instructed its
employees to discourage blacks from joining the Holiday Spas and
offering less favorable membership terms.
   The company operates spas in Maryland, Virginia, Massachusetts,
New Jersey, Pennsylvania and Georgia as well as the District of
Columbia.
   In one report, the Justice Department found that a manager in
Media, Pa., told employees ``whites won't patronize a place if there
is a mix of races,'' the report said.
   A reporter's telephone call seeking comment from the company was
not immediately returned.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Number Of Workers Hired Declines Sharply In January</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Poor weather conditions helped push the number
of workers hired by farmers down to an estimated 701,000 in January
from 976,000 last October, the Agriculture Department said.
   The report released Friday said ``substantial rains'' occurred
during the Jan. 8-14 week when the labor survey was made, from
eastern Texas into the middle Atlantic states.
   Average pay for all workers hired directly by farmers was $5.51
per hour, up from $5.18 during last fall's survey week of Oct. 9-15.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Honey Output Down 7 Percent Last Year</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honey production dropped 7 percent last year to
212 million pounds.
   The Agriculture Department said Friday that about 3.2 million
colonies produced honey in 1988, a decline of less than 1 percent.
But the yield of honey per colony dropped to 66.4 pounds, down from
71.1 pounds in 1987.
   ``Some states had excellent production while production in other
states suffered from drought and disease,'' the USDA report said.
</TEXT>
