<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINONA, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Minnesota couple's attempt to perform one
of David Letterman's ``Stupid Human Tricks'' didn't exactly go as
planned, but it certainly qualified for the title.
   Police had to rescue Robert Cerney and Debbie Burmeister after
they folded themselves, naked, into a collapsible sofa bed and
couldn't get out.
   Authorities say Cerney and Ms. Burmeister were trying to
replicate a feat performed by a La Crosse, Wis., man on ``Stupid
Human Tricks,'' an offshoot of ``Stupid Pet Tricks'' on Letterman's
late-night television show.
   However, the Wisconsin man, David Berg, managed to extricate
himself from his spring-loaded trap. In the copycat attempt, Ms.
Burmeister was only able to free enough of her body to reach a
telephone and summon help.
   Sgt. Dave Gabbert of the Winona Law Enforcement Center said he
was amazed that the couple could fit into a folded sofa bed. But he
advised thrill-seekers not to try it for themselves.
   ``I wouldn't do it,'' Gabbert said. ``I guess that's why they
call it `Stupid Human Tricks.'''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters can't put Jack in the box.
   Jack _ yes, just plain Jack _ was an announced write-in candidate
for City Council. He wanted voters to insert Jack in the write-in
box on their ballots.
   But the city attorney decreed Thursday that just Jack wasn't
enough _ single-monikered candidates are ineligible. For Jack, whose
last name is McGrath, the ruling is yet another obstacle on a rough
and rocky campaign trail.
   McGrath, a 43-year-old commercial real estate agent, started the
political season as an aide to Steve Saltzman, who was running for
the 5th District seat. At the time, incumbent Zev Yaroslavsky
planned to challenge Mayor Tom Bradley for his job.
   Then Yaroslavsky dropped out of the mayor's race and announced
plans to run for re-election. So Saltzman dropped out. And McGrath _
er, Jack _ dropped in.
   When he failed to get the 500 signatures needed to land his name
on the ballot, McGrath launched the write-in campaign, saying he'd
run as Jack so supporters would have an easier time writing him in.
   The City Clerk's office objected and referred the issue to the
city attorney's office. The decision: Jack's not legit.
   ``There must be thousands of Jacks in the city,'' said Deputy
City Attorney Tony Alperin.
   McGrath said he was considering a challenge to the ruling, but in
the meantime the name to write in is Jack McGrath.
</TEXT>
