<FILEID>AP-NR-02-11-89 0235EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Scandal     02-11 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Scandal,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>Election To Test Scandal's Damage To Takeshita Administration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE KURTENBACH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A by-election Sunday is seen as a test of the damage
done to Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita's party by a stock-trading
scandal that has forced the resignation of three Cabinet members.
   The governing Liberal Democratic Party is battling hard to retain
the party's control of a parliament seat of a member who died Dec.
23.
   The voting, on the southern island of Kyushu, is the first
election to a national office since the scandal began last summer.
   Some newspapers predict the leading opposition group, the Japan
Socialist Party, could win, dealing a serious blow to the Liberal
Democrats.
   Suspicions of bribery and influence-peddling have Takeshita
facing opposition pressure to resign or to at least account for his
links to the information services conglomerate Recruit Co.
   The election in Kyushu is viewed as an indicator of what could
happen in July elections for half the upper house, where the Liberal
Democrats hold 143 of the 251 seats.
   Severe setbacks in the elections would endanger Takeshita's
chances next October to win another two-year term as party president
and prime minister, commentators say.
   A poll conducted by Japan's largest newspaper, the Yomiuri
Shimbun, shows Socialist Sadao Fuchigami with a slim lead over the
Liberal Democrats' Kei Oma, the newspaper reported Friday.
   Two other opposition candidates _ Tatsuzen Fujino of the Japan
Communist Party and Kozo Maeda of the Salaried Workers' New Party _
are also contesting the seat.
   The uproar over Recruit began when it was discovered that founder
Hiromasa Ezoe sold unlisted shares in the Recruit subsiary at
bargain prices to more than 150 influential politicians,
bureaucrats, journalists and businessmen before the shares began
trading publicly in October 1986.
   Share prices rose sharply then, and some shareholders gained more
than $80,000 in profits that were tax free because Japan has no
capital gains tax.
   The scandal has cost Takeshita three Cabinet ministers and his
popularity has plunged, prompting him to announce a review of
government ethics.
   ``I have vowed to myself that I must honestly accept the harsh
criticism ... must join hands with you, and must restore the
people's trust in politics,'' Takeshita told parliament Friday. He
called political reform his ``No. 1 priority issue.''
   Many lawmakers say without campaign finance reform, nothing can
be done to remove the network of obligations and expenses that
traditionally link businessmen and politicians.
   Japan is a gift-giving society, and politicians gain voter
support by presenting cash gifts at funerals and weddings of their
constituents.
   A typical legislator also has to spend more than $790,000 a year
on personnel, office rental, phone and mailing costs, said Liberal
Democratic lawmaker Kazuo Aichi in a letter to his constituents.
   The government pays salaries of only two staff members, and no
matching government funds exist to help finance campaigns.
   Politicians devote enormous efforts to raising money, leaning on
businesses and colleagues to buy tickets to fund-raising parties. In
return, business circles expect some political influence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
