<FILEID>AP-NR-02-11-89 0436EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Paraguay     02-11 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Paraguay,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rodriguez Accepts Presidential Endorsement, Opposition Rally Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM H. HEATH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Andres Rodriguez, the leader of
last week's coup, has accepted the governing party's endorsement for
president in elections scheduled for May 1. Opposition leaders
meanwhile planned a rally today to postpone the balloting.
   The acceptance Friday by Rodriguez came one week after he
engineered a military coup that toppled Alfredo Stroessner,
Paraguay's president since 1954, and left at least 50 people dead.
Stroessner, 76, was exiled Monday to Brazil.
   Today's demonstration was to press the opposition's demand that
the elections for president and congress be postponed six months to
give them time to organize a campaign against the Colorado Party,
which has held power in this landlocked country since 1947.
   Scheduled to attend the rally are former Arizona Gov. Bruce
Babbitt; Rep. Bruce Morrison, D-Conn.; and Robert White, U.S.
ambassador to Paraguay in the Carter administration, said Gustavo
Riart, spokesman for the National Accord opposition coalition.
   As ambassador, White had enraged the Stroessner regime by
supporting opposition groups and making pro-democracy statements
that offended Paraguay's leadership.
   White was beaten by Paraguayan police at Asuncion's airport when,
as former ambassador, he accompanied Domingo Laino as the opposition
leader attempted to return to his homeland in 1986. Authorities put
White on the first flight out of the country.
   Rodriguez's candidacy was announced by Conrado Pappalardo,
secretary-general of Government House.
   ``Juan Ramon Chaves and Luis Maria Argana offered Gen. Rodriguez
the candidacy on the occasion of the first meeting of the national
Cabinet, and the president accepted,'' Pappalardo said.
   Chaves is president of the Colorado Party and Argana, a former
Supreme Court president and initial front-runner, is foreign
minister. Rodriguez appointed both hours after his soldiers forced
Stroessner out of power.
   Pappalardo repeated the provisional government's intention to
hold elections May 1.
   Euclides Acevedo, president of the leftist Revolutionary
Febrerista Party, said some opposition groups may boycott elections
they aren't allowed more time to organize for what would be the
first participation in elections for some.
   The rally was set before Stroessner's ouster. Its initial purpose
was to protest alleged fraud in February 1988 elections in which
Stroessner and his Colorado Party won a lopsided eighth straight
victory.
   Rodriguez and Argana say that under the constitution, elections
must be held within 90 days. The opposition argues that the
constitution is suspended since the provisional government seized
power in a coup.
   U.S. Ambassasdor Timothy L. Towell went to the Foreign Ministry
on Thursday to communicate U.S. recognition of the new government.
Towell said he stressed policies in favor of human rights and
democracy and against drug trafficking.
   He told reporters, ``We will be judging the quality of our
relations on the degree in which they move forward in all of these
areas.''
</TEXT>
