<DOCNO> AP890211-0038 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-11-89 0503EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Indonesia-Earthquake     02-11 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Indonesia-Earthquake,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>No Injuries Reported In Series Of Indonesian Quakes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A series of earthquakes hit eastern
Indonesia but no serious damage or injuries were reported,
meteorological officials said today.
   Putu Puja, an official in the Meteorology Office, said about 25
tremors were recorded Friday night. He said one tremor in the Maluku
Sea about 95 miles east of Bitung in North Sulawesi measured a
preliminary 6.0 on the Richter scale. Bitung is about 1,440 miles
northeast of Jakarta.
   ``About 25 tremors were recorded, but there were no reports of
damage or casualties,'' Puja said.
   The National Earthquake Information Center, operated by the U.S.
Geological Survey at Golden, Colo., said it recorded an earthquake
measuring 6.9 on the Richter scale in the Taluad Island, about 900
miles southeast of the Philippines. There were no initial reports of
damage or casualties.
   The Richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by an
earthquake, as measured by the ground motion recorded on a
seismograph. Every increase of one number means that the ground
motion is 10 times greater.
   A quake of magnitude 6 can cause severe damage in populated
areas. A quake of magnitude 7 is considered a major earthquake,
capable of widespread, heavy damage in populated areas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
