<DOCNO> AP890211-0039 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-11-89 0533EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-MultipleTransplants     02-11 0635</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Multiple Transplants,0653</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cancer Patients Saved By Multiple-Organ Transplants</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PG1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A computer operator who is one of 11 formerly
terminal cancer patients saved by revolutionary transplant surgery
says the multiple-organ operation was her only hope of survival.
   ``I probably had a couple more months'' of life left, Diana
Hancock, 40, of Burlington, Wis., said Friday from her room at
Presbyterian-University Hospital. ``This was a future for me.''
   Ms. Hancock and 10 others are living free of malignancy after
receiving four new abdominal organs and being left with little or no
stomach, said transplant pioneer Dr. Thomas E. Starzl of the
University of Pittsburgh.
   ``We're pushing ourselves to the limit,'' Starzl said in an
interview.
   The transplants, believed to be the first of their kind, have
been performed on 10 men and three women since June at
Presbyterian-University. Two patients died, one of them following a
second transplant, Starzl said.
   ``It's a phenomenal accomplishment,'' said Dr. Israel Penn,
professor of surgery at the University of Cincinnati, who keeps a
worldwide transplant tumor registry. ``To keep patients alive
successfully with a big operation like this indicates that
transplantation is really advancing.''
   All 13 patients were near death and their tumors were inoperable,
Starzl said. All but the most recent survivors, including Ms.
Hancock _ who underwent the surgery Jan. 13 _ are home. The latest
transplant was performed Monday.
   Surgical teams removed each patient's liver, pancreas, most or
all of the stomach, two-thirds of the colon, and the duodenum, a
10-inch-long section of the small intestine.
   The cavity was filled with a block of organs consisting of the
liver, pancreas, duodenum and jejunum, a few feet of section of the
small intestine.
   The stomach was not replaced since it is non-essential for
digestion, which can be performed by intestines, Starzl said.
   Because she has no stomach, Ms. Hancock must eat six small meals
a day spaced an hour or two apart. Half a sandwich easily fills her
up.
   ``You try not to drink with your meals because liquid takes up
the space. You know when you've had enough,'' said Ms. Hancock, who
expects to be discharged in a few days.
   Starzl said the procedure is ``a mini-version'' of the five-organ
transplants performed next door at Children's Hospital of Pittsburgh
on two 3-year-olds. Tabatha Foster of Madisonville, Ky., survived
six months before dying in May 1988 and Rolandrea Dodge of
Fruitland, N.M., died last month, six weeks after surgery.
   Both girls died of lymphoproliferative disease, an abnormal
proliferation of lymphoids, or white blood cells, that obstructed
the liver, officials said. Each had received a new liver, pancreas,
stomach, small intestine and part of a large intestine.
   ``We need better tools'' such as anti-rejection medication for
transplants involving the entire digestive system, Starzl said. ``We
need to be able to manage these so-called lymphoids.''
   Abdominal transplantation involving multiple organs ``is not an
all-or-none procedure,'' he said. ``The soundness of the surgery is
exemplified by the (13) procedures.''
   As of Dec. 31, about 1,100 people with malignant tumors had
undergone liver, kidney, heart or bone marrow transplants worldwide,
according to Penn. Eight months of cancer-free survival following a
multiple-organ transplant is ``revolutionary,'' he said.
   ``What he's trying to do is ... remove the entire tumor plus all
areas where it's most likely to spread to in hopes of curing the
cancer altogether,'' Penn said. ``There's one catch _ if the cancer
has spread (undetected) beyond the limits of his dissection.''
   Starzl said he is limiting the new procedure, at least for now,
to cancer patients less than 45 years old.
   ``It's a limited operation at present. We have to see what
happens,'' said Dr. Lewis Teperman, part of the transplant team.
``But I think it's a giant step forward.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
