<HEAD>Soviet Embassy Couple Defect To United States</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States has granted political
asylum to two Soviet citizens who defected to the U.S. Embassy in
Bangkok, an embassy spokesman said today.
   Thai newspapers today identified the defectors as Vladimir Zhila,
a physician attached to the Soviet Embassy in Bangkok, and his wife,
Olga.
   ``Two Soviet citizens approached the American embassy seeking
asylum in the United States,'' said Ross Petzing, spokesman for the
U.S. Embassy. ``The U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service
determined they are refugees and they left for the United States
this morning.''
   Petzing gave no other details.
   Two Thai newspapers, The Nation and The Bangkok Post, reported
that the couple had been missing since Wednesday, when they drove
from the embassy on their way to a hospital.
   Zhila took up his embassy post late last year, the papers said.
   Last month, the United States granted asylum to a Soviet merchant
sailor who jumped ship in Bangkok.
