<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     02-11 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snow in Michigan, Mostly Fair Elsewhere</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Snow was falling in Michigan and Colorado early today, but the
rest of the country enjoyed fairly nice weather as the cold spell
that gripped the nation much of the week faded away.
   Conditions were a bit chilly over the Great Lakes and the
Northeast.
   Temperatures in the teens and 20s combined with gusty winds to
produce wind chills around 10 below zero over parts of northern New
England, Pennsylvania and New York this morning.
   Winds gusted to 40 mph at Buffalo, N.Y., and 35 mph at Detroit.
   Snow continued in Michigan as another weak cold front moved
through. A snow and blowing snow advisory was posted for northwest
lower Michigan and eastern upper Michigan.
   Southwest winds ahead of the cold front shifted lake effect snow
over New York.
   Snow also fell this morning over portions of western Colorado,
northern Utah and southeast Idaho. Rain showers were scattered over
northern California and western Oregon.
   Dense fog in central California reduced visibility at Sacramento
to zero.
   Today's forecast called for scattered snow showers over portions
of the Great Lakes, New York and northern New England. Snow showers
also were expected over western Pennsylvania, with rain or snow
showers across West Virginia.
   Scattered snow showers were expected from northeast Nevada
through northern and central Utah into western Colorado.
   High temperatures were expected in the 30s or 40s across much of
the nation.
   Highs in the 20s were forecast over the northern Rockies, the
northern Plains through the upper Mississippi Valley to the upper
Great Lakes and over northern New England. Readings were expected in
the 50s and 60s from much of California across the southern Rockies,
the southern Plains, the lower Mississippi Valley and Gulf Coast
region into the southern Atlantic states and the northern half of
Florida.
   Temperatures were to reach the low to mid 70s across southern
Arizona, the Rio Grande Valley of Texas and southern Florida.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 3
degrees at Havre, Mont., to 67 at Key West, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 29 fair; Boston 21 partly cloudy; Buffalo 26 snow;
Charleston, S.C. 29 fair; Cincinnati 28 cloudy; Cleveland 28 partly
cloudy; Detroit 25 windy; Miami 59 fair; New York 28 fair;
Philadelphia 25 fair; Pittsburgh 25 partly cloudy; Portland, Maine
17 cloudy; Washington 25 partly cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 10 fair; Chicago 19 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 42
fair; Denver 33 cloudy; Des Moines 25 cloudy; Indianapolis 30 fair;
Kansas City 33 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 19 fair; Nashville 30
fair; New Orleans 38 fair; St. Louis 35 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 42 partly cloudy; Anchorage 31 cloudy; Las
Vegas 42 fair; Los Angeles 51 fair; Phoenix 56 fair; Salt Lake City
24 foggy; San Diego 51 fair; San Francisco 45 fair; Seattle 36
partly cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 21 snow; Toronto 23 windy.
</TEXT>
