<FILEID>AP-NR-02-11-89 0546EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-UN-Israel     02-11 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UN-Israel,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNIFIL Officer Reprimanded For Comparing Israeli Actions to Nazis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Swedish commander of the U.N.
peacekeeping force in south Lebanon has reprimanded a Norwegian
officer for comparing Israeli army actions there to those of the
Nazis in World War II, a U.N. source said.
   The source at UNIFIL, or the U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon, said
Maj. Gen. Lars-Eric Wahlgren reprimanded Lt. Col. J.E. Karlsen,
commander of the Norwegian battalion, on Thursday. He spoke on
condition of anonymity and did give any other details.
   Karlsen made the remark Feb. 2 during a private meeting between
Israeli and UNIFIL officers to discuss the expulsions of 79 Lebanese
villagers from Israel's self-declared security zone in southern
Lebanon. It was leaked to Israeli media.
   The Israeli Foreign Ministry initially protested Karlsen's
remark, then demanded his removal after he said in a newspaper
interview that the comparison succeeded in drawing attention to the
expulsion of the Lebanese villagers.
   ``In World War II my fellow countrymen sacrificed their lives in
the struggle against the Nazis who were trying to expel Jews from
Norway. Nowadays you behave in south Lebanon exactly as the Nazis
did,'' Karlsen was quoted as saying.
   UNIFIL spokesman Timur Goksel, reached by telephone, said
Wahlgren called Karlsen to an hourlong meeting at the force
headquarters in the southern border town of Naqoura. He refused to
elaborate.
   Sixty-five of the deportees were from UNIFIL's
Norwegian-patrolled zone.
   Lebanon has lodged a complaint with the U.N. Security Council
against the expulsions.
   Lebanon's Foreign Ministry said 37 of those expelled were from
the Sunni Moslem village of Shibaa, which refused to cooperate with
the Israeli-supported south Lebanon army militia that patrols the
security zone with Israeli troops.
   The 5,800-strong UNIFIL, drawn from nine nations, mans a narrow
strip north of the security zone. It has been deployed in south
Lebanon since March 1978.
   Israel carved out the six-to-10-mile-wide strip when it withdrew
the bulk of its occupation army from south Lebanon in 1985.
   The strip, which extends from the Mediterranean coast in the west
to the slopes of Mount Hermon in the east, serves as a buffer
against cross-border guerrilla attacks into northern Israel.
</TEXT>
