<FIRST>r i PM-Mexico-Inflation     02-11 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mexico-Inflation,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inflation Inches Upward In Mexico, Capital Flight Stops</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government says the lowest January price
rise in 11 years and the return to Mexico of about $700 million in
capital last month is proof its anti-inflation plan is working.
   The Bank of Mexico said consumer prices rose 2.4 percent in
January, the lowest for that month since 1978, the government
newspaper El Nacional reported Friday.
   The National Consumer Price Index rose by 0.9 percent the latter
half of the month, the central bank said. Higher prices for
services, rents, telephones, medicines and automotive insurance
rates spurred January inflation, it said.
   Still, inflationary momentum has inched upward in recent months,
with prices rising by 2.1 percent in December. The previous highest
monthly inflation rate was 3.1 percent in April.
   The government froze wages, prices and the peso exchange rate in
February 1988 in a bid to curb inflation that reached a record 159.2
percent in 1987.
   Consumer prices rose by 51.7 percent last year under the plan.
   The central bank, in its monthly publication, said an estimated
$700 million in capital returned to the country last month.
   It said investors were encouraged by a gradual peso currency
devaluation instituted on Jan. 1 and lower domestic interest rates.
The devaluation has averaged one peso per day.
   Analysts have said the government adopted the devaluation to
thwart investor speculation that it was planning a major, one-time
currency adjustment.
   Mexico's international reserves plunged from $16 billion in April
to less than $10 billion by December, according to private estimates.
   The run on reserves was attributed to fears of currency
devaluation, pre-payments of private sector foreign debts and
depressed revenues from oil, Mexico's leading export commodity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
