<FILEID>AP-NR-02-11-89 0558EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Nicaragua-Summit     02-11 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nicaragua-Summit,0598</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ortega Sounds Conciliatory Before Summit; Opposition Skeptical</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated PressWriter</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega has been trying
to tidy his economic and political house before a regional summit
Monday, mindful that Nicaragua needs international help to save
itself from economic disaster.
   But the opposition said Ortega's proposals are merely window
dressing and do not seriously address the political problems at the
heart of Nicaragua's economic crisis.
   Ortega, in meetings with opposition parties, raised the
possibility of reforming electoral laws, calling early elections and
granting amnesty to members of deposed President Anastasio Somoza's
National Guard, the official Sandinista newspaper Barricada said
Friday.
   Thousands of guardsmen were imprisoned after the Sandinistas took
power in 1979, and in December the government said it still had more
than 1,700 guardsmen in custody and 1,300 captured anti-Sandinista
rebels.
   On Wednesday, the leftist Sandinista government made another
conciliatory gesture, allowing two former Somoza military officers
to leave the country after they had spent nearly 10 years at the
Venezuelan Embassy under political asylum.
   An 18-month-old regional peace plan, which Ortega and the
presidents of El Salvador, Honduras, Guatemala and Costa Rica will
try to revive at their summit, calls for democratic reforms,
amnesties for political prisoners and talks with the internal
opposition in the five countries.
   Ortega goes into the summit believing his forces have all but
beaten the U.S.-supported guerrilla movement, although scattered
fighting still occurs.
   The United States and Central American nations have been
demanding Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government make more
democratic reforms, as promised.
   ``If in Nicaragua there is no democratization, there won't be a
lasting peace,'' Ariel Bravo of the opposition Marxist-Leninist
Party said in an interview Friday.
   ``If the government agrees to allow freedom of expression, the
capitalists will start investing, the market comes alive,'' Bravo
said. ``That's what they (businessmen) want: a guarantee.''
   The opposition Nicaraguan Democratic Coordinate said Friday that
the government failed to comply with the regional peace plan while
making it appear it is seeking business and opposition support for
recent austerity measures ``under the guise of a pretended economic
and political agreement.''
   The coalition of private business groups, labor unions and
political parties also urged the government to agree to
constitutional reforms to ensure freedom of expression and changes
in laws that now ``guarantee Sandinista control over the results of
any election.''
   Elections for posts from president to town mayors are scheduled
for November 1990.
   Nicaragua needs the injections of money that Western lending
markets can provide. Those sources dried up after the United States
imposed a trade embargo on Nicaragua in 1985, four years after the
rebels began receiving U.S. military aid.
   The ruling Sandinista National Liberation Front is firmly in
power, but its rule could be threatened by the sharp budget cuts and
layoffs it has outlined to contain runaway inflation.
   Inflation rates reached 20,000 percent last year and exports have
fallen for five years.
   Ortega goes to the summit in dire need of foreign aid and loans
for Nicaragua that might be forthcoming only after political
reforms. Opposition and business groups have taken a wait-and-see
attitude toward the government's apparent attempts at rapprochement.
   ``Everybody talks about credibility,'' said Bravo. ``The
Sandinistas have lied to us so many times we don't believe them
anymore.''
   Ortega recently spoke of consolidating Nicaragua's ``historical
victory'' over the Contra rebels and of normalizing relations with
the new Bush administration, which he called more pragmatic than
that of former President Reagan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
