<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Antarctica,0147</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Satellite To Study Unusual Central Antarctica Area</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has launched what it says is the
first satellite to photograph central Antarctica and its unusual
land and ice formations, Tass reported today.
   The official Soviet news agency said Cosmos-2000, launched
Friday, will map the middle Antarctica area and gather data on its
ice and rocks. It will also investigate a hole in the ozone layer of
the atmosphere that scientists believe is caused by pollution.
   Yuri Kiyenko, head of the research and production center Priroda,
which means nature in Russian, said the satellite has entered a
difficult orbit.
   ``This is why not a single spacecraft yet photographed those
areas,'' Tass quoted Kiyenko as saying.
   The center apparently developed the spacecraft.
   Antarctica is the fifth largest continent, with an area of 5
million square miles.
