<FIRST>r i PM-SriLanka     02-11 0284</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>15 Killed In Last 24 Hours</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six Tamils were killed in a clash
between rival militant groups in northern Sri Lanka, and nine other
people died in attacks blamed on Sinhalese extremists in the last 24
hours, police said today.
   Since early January when campaigning started for Wednesday's
parliamentary elections, more than 1,000 people _ including 13
candidates _ have been killed. Both Sinhalese extremists and Tamil
rebels oppose the government and have vowed to prevent it from
holding elections.
   A 12-year-old girl, Udanee Liyanaga, was killed when a bomb was
hurled at a political rally Friday night in Borella on the eastern
outskirts of Colombo, police said, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   The bomb exploded as supporters of President Ranasinghe
Premadasa's United National Party were lighting firecrackers at the
end of the rally. Twenty people, including five young girls, were
injured.
   Police blamed that attack and a series of shootings throughout
the Sinhalese heartland on the People's Liberation Front.
   The front, composed of ultranationalist Sinhalese, say the
Sinhalese-dominated government has made too many concessions to the
Tamil minority.
   In Mannar, 140 miles northeast of Colombo, six Tamil militants
died in a clash Friday between the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam
and the Tamil Eelam Liberation Organization, police said.
   The Tigers are the largest of the Tamil rebel groups that have
been fighting the government since 1983 for an independent homeland.
   Tamils make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people and
say they are discriminated against by the Sinhalese, who account for
75 percent of the population. More than 8,500 people have died in
the Tamil insurrection.
</TEXT>
