<FILEID>AP-NR-02-11-89 0625EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Cambodia     02-11 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cambodia,0446</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thai Foreign Minister Says Sihanouk Resumes Post</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cambodia's unpredictable Prince Norodom Sihanouk
has decided to retake his post as president of the anti-Vietnam
resistance, Thailand's foreign minister said today.
   Sihanouk resigned ``irrevocably'' one year ago because of
differences with the Khmer Rouge, one of the three factions in the
resistance coalition.
   ``Sihanouk now has resumed his post again as president'' of the
resistance government, visiting Foreign Minister Siddhi Savetsila
told reporters in Beijing.
   Siddhi said the 66-year-old prince conveyed his decision in a
breakfast meeting today at Sihanouk's residence in Beijing.
   An aide to Sihanouk, contacted at the residence, confirmed the
prince was again president of Democratic Kampuchea, the resistance
government.
   Earlier this week Sihanouk met with Khieu Samphan, head of the
Khmer Rouge, and other resistance leaders to map out strategy for
peace talks to be held in Jakarta, Indonesia, later this month.
   At a Thursday news conference, Khieu Samphan and his partners
announced proposals for U.N. personnel to supervise the withdrawal
of Vietnamese troops from Cambodia and the establishment of a
four-party coalition government, which would include the
Vietnam-backed Cambodian government of Hun Sen.
   The resistance leaders, however, did not say anything about
Sihanouk returning to his official position. Despite Sihanouk's
quitting as president, the resistance has continued to regard him as
the only man with enough popular support to unite the nation.
   It was not clear whether Sihanouk had resolved his differences
with the Khmer Rouge. The prince last year cited Khmer Rouge attacks
on his guerrilla army as a main reason for his decision to step down
as president.
   Sihanouk now says the Khmer Rouge must be part of any future
coalition government. But in a statement Friday, he said, ``I
solemnly declare that there is no question of letting Mr. Pol Pot
return to power.''
   Pol Pot was the Khmer Rouge leader when the radical Communists
ruled the country from 1975 to 1978, during which time an estimated
about 2 million of Cambodia's 8 million people died from executions,
famine and civil unrest.
   Vietnam invaded Cambodia in late 1978 to drive the Khmer Rouge
from power.
   The resistance wants a U.N. force to be put in place to ensure
that Vietnam ends its 10-year military incursion in Cambodia and to
keep the peace after the Vietnamese leave.
   Vietnam, which has said it will remove all its troops by
September if a peace settlement is in place, opposes bringing in
foreign military personnel. Vietnam says it has 50,000 troops in
Cambodia but Western estimates are much higher.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
