<FIRST>r i PM-Philippines-Fires     02-11 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-Fires,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Fires Break Out In Manila Area, Thousands Homeless</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three mysterious fires broke out
within hours of each other in metropolitan Manila, leaving thousands
of people homeless, police said today.
   The first fire broke out Friday afternoon in Manila's slum
district of Tondo, touching off an eight-hour blaze that gutted
about 2,000 houses, said arson investigator Sgt. Baltazar Dimagiba.
   The cause of the fire is still under investigation, he said.
   At least three firemen and a woman suffered burns or minor
injuries during the fire, Dimagiba said. He said several people,
mostly children, were missing but there were no reports of deaths.
   Several Manila newspapers reported five people were missing and
presumed to have died in the fire. Radio DZMM reported that among
the dead was a looter who was beaten by irate fire victims and
thrown into the blaze.
   The reports could not be immediately confirmed, Dimagiba said.
   He said firefighters had difficulty in putting out the fire
because hundreds of shanties, made of cardboard and light-wooden
materials, blocked many side streets.
   Dimagiba estimated 2,000 houses were razed in a four-block radius
and up to 15,000 people had been rendered homeless by the fire
because most of the houses are being shared by at least three
families.
   ``They had to share small houses to minimize the cost of
living,'' Dimagiba said.
   Two hours after the fire was put under control, a second fire of
unknown origin began a street away and burned down four other
houses, Dimagiba added.
   In Manila's suburb of San Juan, fire broke out this afternoon on
the first floor of the a 12-story commercial building but firemen on
the scene said the blaze was under control.
</TEXT>
