<FIRST>d a PM-Bush-Rebels     02-11 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Rebels,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Bush Agrees To Continue Supplying Afghan Rebels With Aid</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmitting to fix category code</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush has agreed with advisers that the
withdrawal of Soviet troops from Afghanistan is no reason to cut
military aid to the Afghan rebels, The New York Times reported today.
   ``As long as (Afghan leader) Najibullah holds on, the potential
and risk of Soviet activity is very much alive,'' the Times quoted
an unidentified senior administration official as saying.
   ``If the administration took the policy decision to cut off aid
because of Soviet good behavior, it would be hard to get started
again if the Soviets start up again,'' the official said.
   The Times said Bush accepted the recommendation to continue the
aid as long as the Soviet-backed Afghan government is in power.
   The newspaper said senior foreign policy advisers suggested it at
a Friday meeting of the National Security Council.
   The Times quoted unidentified senior administration officials as
saying that although the Soviets are withdrawing troops from
Afghanistan, they continue to leave behind large amounts of military
equipment.
   Administration officials asserted that the decision does not
reflect a change in policy, but rather a change in emphasis, the
newspaper said.
   ``Our basic policy is support for the resistance,'' a senior
State Department official said. ``Our policy remains one of positive
symmetry.''
   ``We never said our support to the rebels would be proportional
to what the Soviets sent,'' the official added.
   The Soviet Union has repeatedly urged the United States to
discontinue aid to the rebels, especially in light of its withdrawal
earlier this month.
   U.S. aid to Afghan rebels is estimated to have totaled $600
million last year.
</TEXT>
