<FILEID>AP-NR-02-11-89 0708EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-MultipleKillings 2ndLd-Writethru a0477 02-11 0694</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Multiple Killings, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0477,0709</SECOND>
<HEAD>Simmons Convicted of Mass Murder; Sentenced to Die</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, ``Simmons, 48 ...,'' to RESTORE first reference
to Bynum; SUBS 5th graf, ```Eye for ...,'' to DELETE first reference.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL SIMMONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLARKSVILLE, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   R. Gene Simmons was sentenced to death
for murdering 14 members of his family in a rampage that his own
attorney said was motivated by ``a base, primeval and vile human
passion.''
   Simmons, who is already under a death sentence in two related
slayings, was convicted and sentenced in rapid succession Friday,
hours after he stunned jurors by attacking the prosecutor in his
trial.
   Johnson County Circuit Judge John S. Patterson accepted the
jury's recommendation and set the execution for March 16 after
Simmons said he knew of no reason why he should not be immediatedly
sentenced.
   Simmons, 48, who was handcuffed after punching prosecutor John
Bynum earlier in the day, displayed no emotion as jurors returned
the guilty verdicts at 8:30 p.m. He was similarly impassive when
they returned less than three hours later with the sentence of death
by lethal injection.
   ``Eye for eye, tooth for tooth, life for life,'' Bynum said
during closing arguments earlier in the day. ``That's where we are
in this case. That's old and ancient and hard. But that is what we
are down to in this case.''
   The verdict and sentence brought a swift end to a brief trial
that began with jury selection Monday and included just 18
prosecution witnesses. The defense did not present a case.
   In closing arguments, defense attorney John Harris said no
evidence had been presented to prove that Simmons was at his house
when the victims were killed, and said there was no evidence he had
fired the gun that he handed over to authorities when he was
arrested.
   After Simmons was convicted but before he was sentenced, the
defense pleaded with the jury to reject the state's contention that
Simmons killed some of his victims to avoid detection before he
killed them all.
   ``His motive was not to avoid arrest but to satisfy a base,
primeval, and vile human passion _ running amok without regard to
arrest,'' said defense attorney Robert E. ``Doc'' Irwin.
   The 14 family members killed by Simmons included his wife, his
seven children, two of the children's spouses and four
grandchildren. Among them was a 24-year-old daughter with whom
Simmons allegedly had an incestuous relationship.
   Their bodies were found by police on Dec. 28 and Dec. 29, 1987,
in and around Simmons' house 25 miles southeast of Clarksville in
northwest Arkansas. Autopsy reports said they had been shot or
strangled, and had died two to six days before they were found.
   Authorities went to Simmons house following his arrest Dec. 28
after he shot six people, two fatally, at four businesses in nearby
Russellville. Simmons was convicted of murder in those deaths last
May and sentenced to death.
   Simmons waived his right to appeal in that case and pleaded to be
executed as soon as possible. The execution has been delayed,
however, because of a legal challenge by an Arkansas minister.
   Irwin said Simmons has consented to an appeal of the latest
conviction.
   Simmons shocked court observers during a routine conference at
the judge's bench Friday morning when he suddenly lunged between
lawyers and struck Bynum, the prosecutor, in the chin. Simmons
punched again, missed and was subdued by court officers.
   The tape recording of court stenographer Johna Roedenbeck
recorded a voice saying, ``He's trying to get a gun,'' and another
voice saying, ``I've got it.''
   Jurors watched wide-eyed and some relatives of the slain family
members dove for the floor.
   ``We were scared to death,'' said Charlotte Crosston, whose
daughter and son-in-law died in the murder spree. ``Our legs were
like rubber. I'm glad he showed the jury, and I'm glad the jury got
to see what he's really like.''
   Before the trial resumed, Patterson told Simmons he was
disappointed in the defendant's behavior and asked, ``Can you give
me any assurance you'll behave yourself?''
   ``I can, but I don't have anything to say,'' Simmons replied.
</TEXT>
