<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Afghan     02-11 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Afghan,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Last Soviet Motorized Unit In Afghanistan Approaching Border</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The last Soviet motorized unit in Afghanistan
approached the Soviet border as the deadline neared for all the
Kremlin's troops to leave the war-torn country, Radio Moscow
reported today.
   The state radio station said in an English-language broadcast
that the unit went through a mountain passage in the Salang Highway
about 125 miles from the Soviet border. The report did not say how
many troops or what kind of equipment were in the unit or when they
went through the passage.
   The Red Army newspaper Krasnaya Zvezda reported today that the
rear guard of Soviet troops had reached Aibak, 80 miles from the
Soviet border.
   Wednesday is the deadline for Soviet troop withdrawal set in a
U.N.-mediated plan.
   Radio Moscow indicated that with the withdrawal of the last
motorized unit, troops guarding the route were no longer needed.
   ``The patrols posted along the highway to ensure the withdrawal
of all troops will be called off,'' the broadcast said. It added:
``A small group of Soviet servicemen will remain at Kabul airport to
guarantee the safe landing of cargo planes from the U.S.S.R.''
   The Soviet air force has been flying hundreds of tons of flour,
canned meat and other staples into Kabul, Afghanistan's capital, to
help feed the poor. A Soviet officer in Kabul, Col. Pavel Vinokunov,
has said the airlift would continue until Monday, when he and his
men will leave the defense of the airport to Afghan government
forces and return to the Soviet Union.
   Col. Gen. Mikhail Moiseyev, the military chief of staff, has said
the last Soviet soldier will leave Afghanistan on Tuesday.
   An estimated 115,000 Red Army soldiers were in the country when
the Soviet pullout began May 15. Fifty thousand Soviet troops were
reported left in the country last August.
   Krasnaya Zvezda reported as of Friday that 39,093 Soviets had
returned home from Afghanistan, leaving an estimated 11,000 Red Army
troops in the country.
   The Kremlin sent military forces to Afghanistan in December 1979
to help Afghan government forces fight Moslem guerrillas. The
guerrillas began fighting after a Communist coup in Afghanistan in
April 1978.
</TEXT>
