<FIRST>r a PM-Thursday'sChild     02-11 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Thursday's Child,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>Light Winds Delay Yacht In Race Against 135-Year Mark</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sailboat Thursday's Child was a day
behind schedule in its effort to beat the New York-to-San Francisco
record set 135 years ago by the clipper Flying Cloud, but its tired
crew pressed on.
   The yacht had been expected to arrive in San Francisco Bay on
Friday, but that prediction was revised after the sloop made
miserable progress in a limp, northerly breeze.
   Thursday's Child was 197 miles south of the Golden Gate on
Friday, and could arrive here this afternoon, shoreside spokeswoman
Sylvia Wilkerson said, cautioning ``it could be Sunday.''
   The three-man crew was ``very tired'' after being forced into
repeated tacks, Wilkerson said at San Francisco's St. Francis Yacht
Club.
   The crew and a host of enthusiasts had hoped the boat would break
the previous record by 10 days by arriving Friday.
   If the 60-foot yacht arrives Sunday, it would be eight days ahead
of the clipper ship Flying Cloud's 89-day, eight-hour record for the
14,500-mile passage, set in 1854. Thursday's Child left New York on
Nov. 23.
   Chief shoreside coordinator Tony Lush took a philosophical view
of the delay. ``Part of being a sailor is taking what the wind gods
will allow,'' he said. ``We will take what we can get.
   ``She is pure sailboat, absolutely at the mercy of the wind,''
Lush added, noting that Thursday's Child has no engine.
   The delay, however, could make the yacht's entry through the
Golden Gate ever more spectacular.
   A flotilla estimated at 50 to 60 boats was waiting to greet
Thursday's Child on Friday, but if it arrived over the weekend there
could be hundreds in the gala fleet. The Coast Guard plans to have
cutters in the bay to prevent watery chaos.
   Besides owner Warren Luhrs, 44, the sloop is crewed by
professional skipper Courtney Hazleton, 32, and Lars Bergstrom, 54,
who helped design the boat.
</TEXT>
