<SECOND>PM-Italy-Azores Victims,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Bodies Are Returned From Azores</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MIL1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERGAMO, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An air force plane today brought to Italy
the first bodies of Italian tourists killed in the crash of a
Caribbean-bound U.S. charter plane in the Azores.
   None of the 144 people believed aboard the ill-fated Boeing 707
survived Wednesday's crash.
   The 15 coffins were taken off the Hercules C-130 aircraft at
Bergamo airport, where the jetliner of the Smyrna, Tenn.-based
Independent Air Corp. took off.
   A second group of about 50 bodies were scheduled to arrive in
Italy late today or Sunday, according to Carla Bisegna, a Foreign
Ministry spokesman.
   At Belgamo airport, a Red Cross worker stood by as a man knelt
down, placed a hand on a carved wooden casket and burst into tears.
   A priest blessed the coffins, some of which carried name tags
with question marks next to the names. Authorities said some victims
were only tentatively identified.
   The charter flight, which carried a crew of seven Americans, was
bound for a resort in the Dominican Republic. It was about to make a
refueling stop in the Azores, a Portuguese island chain in the
western Atlantic, when it slammed into a fog-covered mountain.
   Authorities are investigating the cause of the crash.
   They have said 137 Italians were aboard.
   Italian media today, however, quoted the Italian ambassador to
Portugal as saying there appears to have been more passengers on the
plane than previously believed.
   ``On that plane, there was a lot more people than what we knew.
How and why will be difficult to understand,'' Ambassador Giovanni
Battistini was quoted as saying by La Repubblica newspaper in Rome.
He did not elaborate.
   State television reported five passports had been found that did
not belong to any of the passengers on the flight manifest, raising
suspicions perhaps there were some last-minute passengers.
   The broadcast said another possibility was the passports were of
married women who used their maiden name in the document but were
listed on the passenger list under their husband's last name.
</TEXT>
