<FIRST>r i PM-Germany-FilmFestival     02-11 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-Film Festival,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Berlin Film Festival Opens With Look To Past</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 1989 Berlin International Film Festival opened
with a look 50 years back to a conflict that divided Europe and
engulfed the world.
   West Berlin Culture Senator Volker Hassemer, in opening the
festival Friday, praised the German Kinemathek foundation for
preparing the memorial series ``Europa 1939,'' comprised of 50 films
produced that year in 10 European countries.
   Nazi Germany invaded Poland on Sept. 1, 1939, and World War II
began.
   The exhibit is coupled with a retrospective tribute to
German-American producer Erich Pommer, who fled Germany when Adolf
Hitler took power. The festival will screen 34 of Pommer's works.
   Twenty-two full-length feature films are entered in the main
``Golden Bear'' competition, with U.S. filmmakers out front with
four entries.
   The 12-day festival combines the international competition for
the award for best new feature film with a number of other contests,
premieres, exhibits and markets.
   The U.S. entries include ``Mississippi Burning,'' about the civil
rights movement and the fear and hatred that swept the South a
quarter century ago; ``Talk Radio,'' Oliver Stone's story of a
late-night talk show host driven by ambition to exploit his lonely
listeners; ``The Accused,'' Jonathan Kaplan's account of a gang rape
and its legal aftermath; and ``Rain Man,'' about the relationship
that evolves between an autistic man and his self-seeking younger
brother.
   Other entries include ``The Summer of Aviya'' directed by
Israel's Eli Cohen. The film focuses on a young girl who learns to
cope with the mental instability of her mother, a survivor of the
Auschwitz concentration camp.
   Also showing is ``Hope and Pain,'' by Japanese director Yoji
Yamada.
   Running throughout the festival will be 30 new full-length West
German films and 46 from other nations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890211-0061 </DOCNO>
