<FIRST>r a PM-PreschoolMolest     02-11 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Preschool Molest,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Buckey Cleared for Jail Release on Bail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge set strict conditions for a defendant
in the McMartin preschool child molestation case who is about to be
freed after five years beyind bars without a conviction.
   Superior Court Judge William Pounders delayed the release of
Raymond Buckey until some paperwork is completed, but told him
Friday that he would have to stay away from defendants in the case
and all youngsters under 14.
   The judge also told Buckey that he would be forbidden to return
to the Manhattan Beach area where he was reared and where the
family-run preschool operated.
   ``If you fail to return for trial, the trial will take place in
your absence,'' the judge warned. He said friends of Buckey's who
posted their property to support the $1.5 million bail would lose
their real estate if he failed to appear.
   Attorneys said Buckey, who had been scheduled for release Friday,
probably won't be freed until late next week.
   Deputy District Attorney Lael Rubin, who has objected strenuously
to the defendant's release, said she is satisfied with the
conditions set by the judge, particularly those barring him from
contact with young children.
   Buckey, 30, and his mother, Peggy McMartin Buckey, 61, are being
tried on 65 molestation and conspiracy counts involving 11 children.
Buckey alone is named in 52 of the charges.
   He is the only one of seven original defendants who has been held
in prison while the case crawled through the courts.
   The McMartin case burst into the national media spotlight in 1983
with lurid tales of mass sexual abuse, devilish rituals, death
threats and animal mutilations. Hundreds of children were said to be
involved.
   But at the end of an 18-month preliminary hearing, charges were
dismissed against five teachers when the district attorney concluded
there was insufficient evidence to prosecute them.
</TEXT>
