<SECOND>PM-Korea-Students,0213</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radical Students Clash With Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 500 students demanding the
release of political detainees threw rocks at riot police in
downtown Seoul today and tried to march to a government prosecutor's
office.
   Police tossed about a dozen tear-gas grenades and dispersed the
demonstrators in about 40 minutes. One dissident said at least 27
people were arrested.
   After a two-hour rally at Myongdong Cathedral, protesters
shouting ``release prisoners'' and ``arrest Chun Doo-hwan'' clashed
with riot police on a narrow shopping street.
   Chun, a former South Korean president, has been sharply
criticized recently for purported abuses of power during his
seven-year adminstration.
   The demonstrators also demanded that the government ``tell the
truth'' about the 1980 uprising in Kwangju.
   The government says 200 students were killed and at least 1,000
injured in the revolt, but critics say the numbers are much higher
and have demanded another investigation.
   Dozens of people were pushed and kicked as lines of students
tried unsuccessfully to ram their way past police, who repelled the
protesters with tear-gas grenades.
   Unlike most recent anti-government demonstrations, the protesters
did not use firebombs.
   On Friday, the government proposed legislation that would outlaw
the use or manufacture of firebombs.
