<FIRST>r a PM-ShipCollision 1stLd-Writethru a0485 02-11 0566</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ship Collision, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0485,0575</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Missing, 13 Injured After Cruise Ship Slices Cuban Freighter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to update with ship back in port, safety
inspections planned, picks up 9th graf, `Two lifeboat...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A luxury liner that sliced a Cuban freighter in two,
leaving three crewmen missing and 13 injured, returned to its home
port today while officials asked why the smaller vessel didn't show
up on the liner's radar.
   The cruise ship Celebration's crew said there was no way to avoid
slamming into the cargo ship, which was drifting without lights off
the Cuban coast before dawn Friday, said Carnival Cruise Lines Vice
President Robert Dickinson.
   ``It was not seen on radar. That's a mystery at this point,''
Dickinson said. Navigation lights on the Cuban freighter Capitan San
Luis went on only when the two ships were very close, he said.
   The 734-foot Celebration's officers tried to reverse course, but
it was too late for the 350-foot cement hauler, according to
Dickinson.
   The Miami-based cruise ship suffered minor damage and none of its
1,500 passengers and 600 crew members was injured, he said.
   A large black scrape was visible on the port side from the water
line to the tip of the bow when the Celebration approached its dock
at the Port of Miami today, but Carnival spokesman Tim Gallagher
said it looked worse than it was.
   Accident investigations were planned by the cruise line and its
insurer, Lloyd's of London, as well as the National Transportation
Safety Board, which has conducted a series of hearings in Miami on
cruise line safety.
   A team from the Coast Guard's marine safety office also planned
to inspect the cruise ship, Coast Guard Petty Officer Brian Lincoln
said today. Gallagher was confident the ship would clear that
inspection and sail again as scheduled at 4 p.m. on another weeklong
cruise.
   NTSB officials said they also wanted to look into the incident
even though it involved a Liberian-registered cruise liner and a
Cuban freighter en route from Havana to the Canary Islands.
   ``We don't have jurisdiction, but we are expecting that Carnival
Cruise Lines will grant us permission to go aboard when the ship
arrives,'' NTSB spokesman Michael Benson said in Washington. ``We
want to look at the ship and talk in particular to the crew on the
bridge at the time.''
   Two lifeboat crews from the Celebration rescued 42 of the 45
Cuban crew members, including one whose foot was severed, the Coast
Guard said.
   A Cuban navy frigate and tug picked up the rescued crew members,
who were being treated at Cuba's Comandante Pedro Sotto Alba
Hospital, Cuba's Prensa Latina news agency reported.
   The three missing men were apparently in a cabin at the stern of
the 350-foot freighter, which sank immediately, Coast Guard
spokesman Luis Diaz said. The bow section sank hours later.
   The three missing crewmen included the ship's Capt. Manuel
Velazco Morales, 34, Antonio Campos de los Reyes, 41, and Ivan
Freyre Diaz, 40, all of Havana, Prensa Latina reported.
   ``Basically, we've relinquished our search and rescue
responsibilities to Cuba,'' said Coast Guard spokesman Daniel White.
   At the time of the accident, the Celebration was on its way back
to Miami, ending a seven-day cruise that included stops at San Juan,
Puerto Rico; St. Vincent and St. Martin.
</TEXT>
