<FIRST>r i PM-Afghanistan     02-11 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Despite Optimism, Rebel Leaders Far From Consensus</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Afghan guerrilla spokesman said
today that a meeting to form a post-war Islamic government for his
homeland will reconvene, but others said deep divisions threaten the
process.
   The 526 delegates who gathered Friday to attend the meeting
included guerrillas, scholars and ministers from previous Afghan
governments.
   But the meeting was adjourned indefinitely after Iranian-based
guerrillas walked out in a dispute over representation at the
meeting and on a Supreme Council of guerrilla leaders.
   The Supreme Council would make many day-to-day decisions in the
post-war Afghan government.
   Rasul Sayyaf, spokesman for the gathering, told a news conference
in the Pakistan capital that the meeting would resume but that he
could not say when.
   Sayyaf played down divisions in the quarrelsome alliance of seven
Pakistani-based insurgent groups.
   But guerrilla sources who spoke on condition of anonymity said
the factions were deeply divided over the composition of a post-war
government and the role the eight Iranian-based insurgent groups
would play.
   Earlier this month, Sibghatullah Mojaddidi, chairman of the
Pakistan alliance, offered the Iranian-based groups 100 delegates to
the meeting and six seats on the Supreme Council.
   He was overruled by the Pakistan alliance's four extremist
parties, said Ghulam Waziri, political officer of Mojaddidi's
moderate Afghan National Liberation Front.
   Sayyaf said the last offer to the Iranian alliance was 102
delegates to the meeting, of which 42 would be chosen by the
Pakistani alliance. There was no offer of seats on the Supreme
Council.
   The Iranian alliance also rejected that offer.
   Mohammad Karim Khalili, chairman of the Iranian alliance, said
earlier today his delegation was returning to Tehran.
   The guerrillas based in Iran belong to Afghanistan's minority
Shiite sect of Islam.
   The Pakistani-based insurgents are Sunni Moslems and so are about
80 percent of Afghanistan's 15 million people.
   Officials of moderate guerrilla groups based in Pakistan said
they feared hard-line Islamic radicals would try to dominate a
post-war government.
   ``We don't want an extremist-dominated government to be there,''
said Azim Nasser-Zia, spokesman for the moderate National Islamic
Front of Afghanistan.
   One thing the guerrilla groups agree on is that the communist
government in Afghanistan will fall after the Soviets complete their
troop withdrawal, expected by Wednesday under an accord mediated by
the United Nations.
   The Soviets sent troops to Afghanistan in 1979 to prop up the
Marxist government. About 115,000 soldiers were stationed there when
the Red Army began its pullout in May.
</TEXT>
