<FIRST>u i PM-Kuwait-Terrorists 1stLd-Writethru a0505 02-11 0415</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kuwait-Terrorists, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0505,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two of 17 Convicted Terrorists Released</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines previous urgent series, a0505 and a0507. UPDATES with
more background. No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two of 17 jailed terrorists whose release is the
key demand of kidnappers holding American hostages in Lebanon have
been released after serving five-year prison terms, Kuwait's
interior minister said today.
   Sheik Salem Sabah said the two men _ Abdul-Mohsen Rashash Abbas,
25, an Iraqi national; and 30-year-old Nasser Matar Dahash, whose
family lives in Kuwait without official citizenship _ were released
``a while ago, having completed their prison terms.''
   The pro-Iranian terrorists were convicted of a spate of bombings
in Kuwait in December 1983, including the Dec. 12 attack on the U.S.
Embassy that involved driving a bomb-laden truck into the compound.
Other targets hit in the attacks were the French embassy and Kuwait
airport control tower, an industrial center, the Electricity and
Water Ministry's control center, and offices and residences of
Americans.
   The Arab government reported five people killed, including the
truck driver, and 86 wounded. The U.S. Embassy listed seven killed,
including the truck driver.
   Speaking to reporters today, Sheik Salem said the release ``has
nothing to do with the demands of extremist organizations.''
   The 17 terrorists sent to Kuwaiti jails included three sentenced
to death by hanging, seven to life imprisonment, four to 15 years in
jail, one to 10 years and the two to five years.
   Three others, Iraqi Shiites, were tried and sentenced to death in
their absence.
   They all were sentenced March 27, 1984, by Kuwait's state
security court.
   The terrorists include Kuwaitis, Iraqis and Lebanese, most
belonging to the Shiite branch of Islam, which is the dominant sect
in Iran.
   Islamic Jihad, or Islamic Holy War, a pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem
faction based in Lebanon, had demanded the release of the 17
convicts in return for two American hostages it has been holding
since 1985.
   Those captives are Terry Anderson, 41, of Lorain, Ohio, the chief
Middle East correspondent for The Associated Press; and Thomas
Sutherland, 57, of Fort Collins, Colo., acting dean of agriculture
at the American University of Beirut. Islamic Jihad also claims to
be holding hospital administrator David Jacobsen, 55, of Huntington
Beach, Calif.
   Anderson, kidnapped on March 16, 1985, is the longest-held of 15
Westerners missing in Lebanon. Sutherland was kidnapped June 9, 1985.
   Captors of the other hostages _ including seven other Americans _
have not publicly demanded the release of the Kuwaiti prisoners.
</TEXT>
