<FIRST>r i AM-Hurricane     02-11 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hurricane,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hurricane Harry Hits New Caledonia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NOUMEA, New Caledonia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hurricane with winds up to 125 mph
struck the north coast of this French Pacific island territory
Saturday, causing heavy damage but no injuries or deaths,
authorities said.
   Roads were closed, electricity, water and telephone service were
cut and villages were isolated in the heavy rains dumped on the
archipelego by Hurricane Harry, according to officials in the
capital, Noumea.
   A large number of trees were uprooted, police said.
   The eye of the hurricane passed over the island about 9 p.m., and
the storm seemed to take a turn toward the east, New Caledonia's
weather service reported.
   It blew over Fiji on Friday, killing four people and devastating
several hundred acres of sugar cane, according to the Fiji weather
service.
   In Koumac, 250 miles from Noumea and the largest town in northern
New Caledonia, a school was damaged and a hospital was flooded
during the storm.
   No precise damage estimate was immediately available.
   The airline Air-Caledonia told the French news agency Agence
France-Presse it had canceled all flights to and from New Caledonia,
a group of islands covering 7,335 square miles northeast of
Australia.
   Residents of New Caledonia were warned to avoid traveling on sea
or land and to take measures to protect their homes.
   In early January, Hurricane Delilha caused two deaths and
considerable damage in New Caledonia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
