<SECOND>AM-BRF--Japan-Radicals,0151</SECOND>
<HEAD>Five Ultra-Leftists Arrested in Rally Against Monarchy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 1,000 ultra-leftist radicals shouting slogans
against the monarchy marched through downtown Tokyo on Saturday, and
five were arrested for obstructing police, officials said.
   A Metropolitan Police Department official said several scuffles
broke out during the demonstration, but there were no reports of
serious injuries.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said 940
radicals participated in the march.
   Chanting ``Fight the emperor!'' and ``The final battle!'' the
radicals were surrounded by plainclothes police and riot control
personnel wearing helmets and carrying metal shields.
   Joining in the demonstration were three major radical groups: the
Chukaku-ha, or Middle Core Faction; the Kaiho-ha, or Liberation
Faction, and the Senki-ha, or Battle Flag Faction.
   All three groups have vowed to disrupt the state funeral Feb. 24
for Emperor Hirohito, who died of cancer Jan. 7.
