<FIRST>r i AM-India-Violence     02-11 0205</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Violence,0211</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hindu Found Hanged; Sikhs Suspected</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHANDIGARH, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Hindu laborer was found hanged early
Saturday, apparently the victim of Sikh militants who have vowed to
avenge the executions of two Sikhs convicted in the slaying of Prime
Minister Indira Gandhi, police said.
   Villagers found the victim hanging from a tree at Singh Pura,
about 50 miles southwest of Chandigarh, a Punjab police spokesman
said.
   The man was identified as Nand Lal, according to the official,
who spoke on condition of anonymity. He said no group had claimed
responsibility.
   Lal was the 14th person to be found hanged since Jan. 6, when two
Sikhs were hanged after being convicted in Mrs. Gandhi's 1984
assassination.
   Some of the other victims' bodies were found with notes claiming
responsibility in the names of Sikh separatist groups.
   Radical Sikhs, who are fighting for an independent homeland in
Punjab state, have killed more than 230 people in Punjab so far this
year, according to police.
   Sikhs are a religious minority in India, constituting 2 percent
of the nation's 880 million people, but they are a majority in
Punjab. The militants say they are discriminated against by Hindus,
who make up 80 percent of the national population.
