<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--EiffelRestaurant     02-11 0161</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Eiffel Restaurant,0164</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poor Economy Closes Restaurant That Was Part Of Eiffel Tower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A restaurant that was moved from the Eiffel
Tower in Paris to New Orleans has become the latest casualty of
Louisiana's depressed economy.
   ``We're just not doing enough business now,'' said Daniel P.L.
Bonnot, the restaurant's developer and chef.
   ``New Orleans is a French city with a French history. It's the
perfect place to have a French restaurant like this,'' he said
Thursday in announcing the closure. ``But not with the bad economy
like this.''
   In 1981, Le Restaurant de la Tour Eiffel was removed from its
perch on the Eiffel Tower, 562 feet above the ground, when engineers
noticed the tower was beginning to sag under its weight.
   It opened in 1986 after more than two dozen partners put up about
$3.3 million. Last April, the partners filed for Chapter 13 federal
bankruptcy protection from creditors so they could attempt to
reorganize.
