<FIRST>r a AM-NuclearTest     02-11 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nuclear Test,0225</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Test Of 1989 Conducted In Nevada</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MERCURY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first underground nuclear weapons test
of 1989 was strong enough to shake some highrise buildings in the
gambling city of Las Vegas, 80 miles away.
   Friday's test, code-named Texarkana, had been scheduled for
Thursday but was delayed by snow. It was delayed four hours Friday
by low cloud cover at the Nevada Test Site, a 1,350-square mile
expanse of desert northwest of Las Vegas.
   The weapon, buried 1,650 feet beneath the surface of Yucca Flat,
had an explosive yield equivalent to between 20 and 150 kilotons ot
TNT, said Energy Department spokesman Jim Boyer, who was at the
control center 7.5 miles from ground zero.
   Jan Jackson, a telephone operator at the Regency Towers highrise
apartments in Las Vegas, said chandeliers tinkled shortly after the
blast, but she said it wasn't as strong as some previous shots.
   ``Some of them have been pretty noticeable,'' she said. ``There
were no calls (from residents) but we're getting so used to them, we
don't get calls like we used to.''
   The explosion registered 5.1 on the Richter scale at the National
Earthquake Information Center in Golden, Colo., said spokesman
Waverly Person.
   It was the 688th announced test since testing began at the Nevada
site Jan. 27, 1951.
</TEXT>
