<FIRST>r a AM-TicketsTossed     02-11 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tickets Tossed,0232</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Throws Out Hundreds Of Tickets Because Prosecutor Tardy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge threw out hundreds of traffic
tickets because a prosecutor was a few minutes late, and says he
thinks he's made his point.
   ``Everyone is supposed to be there by 9 a.m. and that applies to
the prosecutor as well,'' Baton Rouge City Court Judge Byron
Stringer said Friday.
   Stringer also issued a bench warrant accusing City Prosecutor
Carl Jackson of contempt, but dismissed it after conferring with
Jackson and deciding no deliberate contempt of court was involved.
   The judge acknowledged that Assistant City Prosecutor Sybil
LeDuff did walk into court about 9:02 or 9:03 a.m. Friday, and said
there has not been any problem with habitual tardiness on the part
of prosecutors.
   But he said he has warned members of the prosecutor's office that
he'd dismiss traffic cases on his docket if prosecutors were late.
   Jackson said the judge never told him personally.
   Stringer said his chief deputy clerk and bailiff both went out in
the hall at 9 a.m. but couldn't find anyone from the prosecutor's
office.
   Jackson said LeDuff, recently hired, was indeed in the hall,
taking tickets from people who had appeared and sorting through
cases to see which would go to trial. It's possible the courtroom
staffers didn't recognize her, he said.
</TEXT>
