<FIRST>u i PM-Taiwan-Jet 4thLd-Writethru   02-11 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Taiwan-Jet, 4th Ld-Writethru,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Taiwanese Jet Fighter Crashes In China</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates thruout with relatives, Chinese officials commenting
on whether pilot is defector, that plane ran out of oil sted gas, number
of defectors from China to Taiwan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jet fighter of the Nationalist Chinese Air Force
crashed in a rice paddy in communist China today after it ran out of
oil, but the pilot parachuted to safety, official reports said.
   In Taiwan, a relative of the pilot said he believed the officer
had defected to China to see his grandmother in the southeastern
province of Guangdong.
   But an official at the Canton office of the state-run radio said
government officials did not believe the pilot, identified as Lin
Xianshun, 35, had defected.
   ``We believe he lost his way in the fog,'' said the official, who
would only identify himself as Wang. ``He now is in the hospital in
Canton with minor injuries.''
   The radio official said provincial officials will meet Sunday to
discuss Lin's repatriation if he is not a defector.
   Air Force officials in Taiwan said the F-5E jet fighter lost
contact with a radio tower at Chihang Air Base, 180 miles southest
of Taipei, about 10 minutes after taking off on a training flight.
   The Canton radio official said the plane crashed in a rice paddy
in Fengshun County about 180 miles north of Canton, the provincial
capital of Guangdong province.
   He said it was not clear whether there were any casualties on the
ground.
   The Xinhua News Agency said the plane was mangled in the crash.
   A relative of Lin, speaking on condition of anonymity from
Miaoli, about 30 miles south of Taipei, said he believed the pilot
had defected because Lin had complained about the ban on military
personnel visiting China.
   In 1987, the Nationalist government in Taiwan eased the ban to
allow all Taiwanese, except military personnel and government
employees, to visit China.
   More than a dozen Nationalist Air Force officers have sought
asylum in China since 1949, when the Nationalists fled to Taiwan
after losing a civil war with communist forces on the mainland.
   The latest was Li Dawei, who defected in 1983 in a trainer plane.
Li received $40,000 from the Chinese government and use of a
chauffered limousine.
   China late last year abolished the system of rewards for
Taiwanese military defectors.
   Military officials in Taiwan said 19 military personnel have
defected from China to Taiwan since 1949.
   China regards Taiwan as a renegade province and the two are
technically at war.
</TEXT>
