<FILEID>AP-NR-02-11-89 1156EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Afghanistan-Pakistan     02-11 0174</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan-Pakistan,0179</SECOND>
<HEAD>Afghan President Says Pakistan Plans to Invade</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHARON HERBAUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Najib today accused Pakistan
of massing troops along the border to invade and later annex
Afghanistan.
   In a speech broadcast on national radio and television, Najib
said his government had received information that Pakistani forces
were preparing to attack the southern Afghan city of Jallabad. He
did not give details.
   ``Militarist and reactionary parties envisage swallowing our
country and turning it into a fifth province of Pakistan,'' the
43-year-old president said in his strongest statement yet against
Pakistan.
   There was no immediate comment from Pakistani officials.
   The seven leading guerrilla groups fighting Afghanistan's
Soviet-backed government are based in Pakistan, their main backer
along with the United States.
   The Soviets are to withdraw the last of their estimated 115,000
soldiers from Afghanistan by Wednesday, and guerrilla leaders have
been struggling to agree on the composition of a new government.
   Many diplomats predict Najib's government will not remain in
power long after the Soviet pullout.
</TEXT>
