<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Rebels     02-11 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Rebels,0612</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebels Say They Can Oust Khomeini, But Others Call It Pipedream</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Iran-Anniversary, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MacFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's main rebel group says it has the
military might to overthrow Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's
government, but analysts dismiss the claim and say the insurgents'
latest raid severely damaged their cause.
   Hussein Mahdavi, a senior official of the Iraqi-based Mujahedeen
Khalq, or People's Holy Warriors, would not say how long it might
take to overthrow Iran's Islamic fundamentalist government, which is
celebrating its 10th anniversary.
   ``If you look at the divisions ... inside the Khomeini regime,
and compare it to the resistance ready at any time to overthrow the
regime, you cannot seriously speak about needing years,'' he said in
a recent interview with The Associated Press. ``We've shown that we
have the ability to militarily overthrow this regime.''
   The Mujahedeen's military arm, the National Liberation Army, made
a large-scale incursion into western Iran just before the Aug. 20
cease-fire in the Iran-Iraq war.
   The rebels still hand out literature by the pound claiming the
raid, called Eternal Light, was a major victory, but diplomats say
Khomeini's Revolutionary Guards soundly beat the insurgents.
   The Mujahedeen is believed to have no more than 15,000 fighters,
and it admits losing 1,000 in the raid. In addition, thousands of
their supporters in Iran were arrested and many were believed
executed.
   Diplomats, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Eternal Light
undermined whatever support the rebels had in Iran.
   Talk of overthrowing Khomeini is ``sheer dreaming and sheer
stupidity'' said one Western military analyst, who spoke on
condition of anonymity. ``What could they do? Where would they go?
They got destroyed in the Eternal Light operation.''
   Much of Iran's civilian population has been moved away from the
border during the Iran-Iraq war, so capturing territory would be a
limited threat to the government, analysts said.
   They argued that since the million-strong, high-tech Iraqi army
could not overwhelm the Iranians in eight years of war, it is highly
unlikely the rebels could.
   Even if the rebels did have an army ready to cross the border,
the analysts said, Iraqi President Saddam Hussein appears committed
to peace negotiations and probably would not allow the insurgents to
attack.
   Iraqi officials declined to comment on the Mujahedeen's future.
   ``Everything on those issues will be dependent on Iranian
behavior,'' said deputy Foreign Minister Nizar Hamdoon. ``It's
premature to address this point at the moment.''
   The Mujahedeen appear to have broad support in Iraq. They still
broadcast a nightly half-hour television program and one diplomat
noted the post office box listed on their official paper is the same
used by the Culture and Information Ministry.
   But Iraq has expelled Iranian resistance groups before. Khomeini
himself spent 15 years in the holy city of Najaf but was asked to
leave in 1978 during a moment of detente in Iran-Iraq relations.
   Mahdavi conceded a peace treaty might mean Iraq would bar the
Mujahedeen from staging military operations across the border. He
would not say if the rebels are conducting operations now.
   The Mujahedeen were allied with Khomeini in the 1979 revolution
that toppled Iran's monarchy. But the fundamentalists turned on
their liberal allies in 1981 and killed thousands in a bloody purge.
   Peace negotiations between Iran and Iraq have been stalled since
November. Mahdavi accused Iran of delaying talks because of internal
differences and said a treaty might trigger a civil war.
   ``At that time the NLA ... will embark on overthrowing the
Khomeini regime,'' Mahdavi said.
</TEXT>
