<FILEID>AP-NR-02-11-89 1242EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     02-11 0783</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0812</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A motto in Latin about grapes and the meaning of
life brought a touch of class to ``Lonesome Dove'' even if Gus
McCrae didn't know what it meant and Latin scholars have differing
interpretations.
   ``It's a motto. ... It just says itself,'' McCrae explained to
his partner, Woodrow F. Call, in Larry McMurtry's Pulitzer
Prize-winning novel.
   But that didn't satisfy the public, which has been clamoring for
an explanation ever since the book was turned into a hit CBS-TV
miniseries, broadcast last week.
   ``We got about 15 to 20 calls the day after the final episode,''
Dallas Public Library researcher Marilyn Jackson said Friday. The
four-day series wound up Wednesday.
   The motto, ``Uva uvam vivendo varia fit,'' appeared on the sign
for the Hat Creek Cattle Company and Livery Emporium. McCrae thought
that whatever it meant, it would lend some dignity to the sign.
   In the TV series, the motto also became McCrae's epitaph as Call
used the remains of the sign to mark his grave.
   Ms. Jackson said researcher Carl Perkins translated the motto as:
``The grape is made manifold by living.''
   Two Latin scholars offered different views.
   Isaac Tennison, a lecturer at the University of Texas-Arlington
,says it's ``A grape becomes mature by living only as a grape.''
   Bruce MacQueen of the University of Dallas translates it as ``A
grape becomes a different kind of grape by living _ or in the
process of living.''
   MacQueen added that the motto was improperly constructed, saying
that under Latin's complex rules for the endings of words, the
``uvam'' should be another ``uva.'' He called it ``a mistake that a
schoolboy who was learning to write Latin might make.''
   Uva or uvam, MacQueen said he was pleased with the interest in
Latin aroused by the story.
   ``We're not going to look any gift publicity in the mouth,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BUG, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The road signs marking a traveler's entry into
the village of Bug have bugged out twice, leaving the man who
lobbied for them _ well, bugged.
   ``Maybe I'll put them up in a tree,'' said Glynn Mann, who
successfully lobbied to have the signs installed and is now trying
to figure out how to thief-proof the next pair of green and white
Bug signs.
   Bug-loving bandits have struck twice, stealing the two signs
within a day after the state installed them last March, and then
stealing the replacements within a few days of their installation in
October.
   ``We appeared and disappeared,'' said Mann's wife, Shirley, who
indulges with good humor her husband's efforts to mark the central
Kentucky village of 50 about 2{ miles north of the
Kentucky-Tennessee line.
   A new set of signs has been ordered but not yet installed as Mann
ponders his next move.
   Bug got its name perhaps a century ago when some men were
standing around trying to decide what to name the new post office,
said 70-year-old Harley Jones, a lifelong resident. ``A bug crawled
across the road, and they said, `We'll call it Bug,''' Jones said.
   Another version of the story, Mann said, is that the men choosing
the name were sitting around in a general store and saw the fateful
bug crawl up the wall.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OCALA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A young man who rides in a limo and wears a
white tuxedo, top hat, red bow tie and dark sunglasses has become a
mysterious hero by handing out $50 bills to charities.
   Salvation Army employees watched in disbelief Friday as the man
gave them the money, then quietly got back into the back seat of a
gray, chauffeur-driven limousine.
   As always, the blond mystery chap made his getaway without
leaving a clue as to his identity. He left only his calling card,
reading: ``Welcome to Paradise.''
   In recent weeks, he has bestowed his largess on five charities, a
hospital, and two citizens.
   But Friday's visit to the Salvation Army was perhaps predictable.
In an article on the mystery man published Thursday in The Ocala
Star-Banner, an official there joked, ``If you find out who he is,
give him our address.''
   Mary Guzan was one of the two private citizens who've gotten $50.
   ``He tried to talk to an older couple, but they turned their back
on him and wouldn't talk to him,'' said Mrs. Guzan, who was in a
restaurant at the time. ``Then he came over and started talking to
us. He said, `I want to give you something because you were nice.'
   ``I kept the card and I haven't spent the money yet,'' she said.
``My husband thinks we should buy a tree and plant it in honor of
him.''
</TEXT>
