<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former basketball coach Dana Kirk, who fell
from grace after leading Memphis State into the national rankings,
has been sentenced to a year in prison for tax evasion and
obstruction of justice.
   ``Nobody knows how much I've been punished. I love that game of
basketball,'' Kirk told a federal judge Friday in asking for
community service work instead of jail time.
   His request was denied and he also was fined $20,000, assessed
prosecution costs for his two-month trial and ordered to serve three
years' probation after he is released from prison.
   He also must pay penalties and back taxes the Internal Revenue
Service says he owes.
   At an hourlong sentencing hearing before U.S. District Judge
Odell Horton, Kirk, 53, apologized for not paying enough attention
to his taxes but continued to claim he did not intend to break the
law.
   ``I just got so involved in my job,'' he said.
   Kirk was fired from Memphis State in 1986 shortly before he was
indicted. He was convicted in November on five counts of a
nine-count indictment.
   During the trial, Kirk was described as a wheeler-dealer who
swelled his annual income from his coach's salary of $62,500 or less
to up to $300,000.
   Witnesses accused him of demanding payments from basketball
tournament promoters, collecting money to pass along to players and
selling basketball tickets.
   Horton did not set a date for Kirk to report to prison, and the
former coach said he still is considering an appeal.
</TEXT>
