<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fans love rock acts such as Sting and
U2. But when love turns to litigation, the stars turn to Walter
Howell.
   Sting and U2 are among several rock acts whose tours are insured
by Howell's company, Birmingham-based W.R. Howell &amp; Associates. The
company also insured last year's Amnesty International tour
headlined by Bruce Springsteen, Tracy Chapman and Peter Gabriel.
   ``Twenty years ago, it was unheard-of for a fan to sue,'' said
Howell, 57. ``But today, that's simply not true. People are more
willing to sue.''
   Howell &amp; Associates had revenues of $8 million in 1988. Costs of
insuring tours vary, depending upon factors such as the number of
stops, Howell said.
   The average rock tour results in five to 10 claims, with the
usual claim seeking up to a few thousand dollars for such things as
tripping and falling when lights are turned low.
   Howell said he attends about 100 concerts a year and estimated
his company is involved with 7,500 to 10,000 concerts a year.
   ``I guess I have to like rock 'n' roll,'' he said, adding he
still has an ear for opera and Frank Sinatra.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The oldest daughter of civil rights activist
Malcolm X stood on her father's birth site for the first time, later
saying that on her flight to Omaha she was touched and felt that her
father was near.
   Attallah Shabazz visited Omaha to talk about the side of her
father that the news media and public rarely saw, she said.
   Malcolm X was born Malcolm Little on May 19, 1925. People often
called him a militant, conjuring negative images of him, Ms. Shabazz
said Friday.
   But by the time he died in New York City in 1965, the victim of
an assassin's bullet, he had become a civil rights and human rights
leader for mankind, not just for black people, she said.
   Malcolm X's birthplace more recently had been a vacant lot. It
now has the first Nebraska state historical marker honoring a black
person, dedicated in 1987.
   Ms. Shabbazz said she was too young to fully realize her father's
rolein history or the impact he had internationally until she was in
college.
   ``I had to learn about him like any other student,'' she said.
