<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-FemaleBishop     02-11 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Female Bishop,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prayer Service For Bishop Harris</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Female Bishop, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Well-wishers filled a London church Saturday to
celebrate the consecration in the United States of a female
Episcopal bishop, the first woman elevated to that rank in the
Anglican Communion.
   Archbishop of Canterbury Robert Runcie, leader of the worldwide
Anglican Communion and spiritual head of the Church of England _
which bars women from the priesthood _ wrote to the Episcopal Church
to say he would pray for it on the day of the Rev. Barbara Harris'
consecration in Boston.
   ``We are deeply conscious that not every Anglican will yet feel
able to acknowledge her as a bishop of the church,'' Runcie said in
his message, which was released to the press.
   The Church of England is divided on the issue of women's
ordination but is committed to moving slowly toward it.
   The issue of a woman achieving the rank of bishop is even more
divisive, and some members of the Anglican clergy and laity say they
will not be able to recognize Harris in her new role.
   Some 250 worshipers, most of them women, filled St. James's
Church in Piccadilly, where the Rev. Sister Denzil said Harris'
consecration gave new hope to the church.
   Some of the worshipers wore badges that read: ``God is an equal
opportunity employer _ shame about the church.''
   ``Layers of fear and prejudice have been broken through and years
of stereotyping have been cast off,'' said Sister Denzil, a nun and
deacon of the Community of St. Andrew in London.
   Harris' position would bring her pain, Sister Denzil said, but
she had been elected to the post by men and women who believed she
was the best person for it.
   The service was organized by the Movement for the Ordination of
Women, Women in Theology, the St. Hilda's Community and Priests for
Women's Ordination.
   The Bishop of Bristol, the Right Rev. Barry Rogerson, said
Saturday that the consecration was a cause for sadness.
   ``We in the Church of England cannot at present receive her
ministry as a bishop and so our fellowship, our communion with one
another, is impaired; our unity is undermined,'' he said.
   The consecration has been criticized by the Evangelical and
Catholic Mission in America and the Association for the Apostolic
Ministry in Britain.
</TEXT>
