<SECOND>AM-Iraq-Soviet,0198</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iraq, Soviet Union Sign Economic Pact</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union will build new power
plants, renovate old ones and set up oil rigs in Iraq under an
accord the two countries signed Saturday, state radio reported.
   Iraqi radio said the agreement was aimed at expanding economic
and technical cooperation between the Soviet Union and the gulf
state.
   Under the agreement, the Soviet Union will build 11
thermoelectric plants and an unspecified number of hydroelectric
power plants, and it will expand several other plants built by the
Soviets in the past 30 years.
   It said the two sides also agreed the Soviet Union will continue
its expansion and development at West Quran oil field, 43 miles
north of the southern port of Basra.
   The accord called for building four new rigs in West Quran, as
well as four others in Iraq's major oil field of al-Rumaila, also
near Basra, the radio said.
   It was signed by Iraq's Oil Minister Issam Abdul-Rahim al-Chalabi
and his Soviet counterpart, Vasily Dinkov.
   Iraq and Iran both have ambitious plans to rebuild their
war-battered countries since they signed a cease-fire Aug. 20.
