<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Rally     02-11 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Rally,0300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protesters Jeer Right-Wing Party Delegates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RAHDEN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 4,000 protesters Saturday
heckled and jeered about 1,000 members of the right-wing German
National Democratic Party as it began a two-day rally.
   Protesters gathered near a hall where delegates met for the party
conference, and 1,000 police officers surrounded the building to
keep the two sides apart, officials said.
   By mid-morning, delegates could no longer reach the hall because
of the protests, police said.
   A police spokesman, Reinhard Stellke, said officers used
spray-can irritants at one point to clear a path for delegates. He
said police, fearing violence, later decided not to escort any more
delegates to the hall.
   Police reported several scuffles and vandalism to cars.
   Stellke said party sympathizers beat one demonstrator as the
protester, but there were no arrests.
   Demonstrators shouted ``Kick the Nazis out!'' and ``Keep the
foreigners, force the Nazis out'' as delegates arrived early
Saturday.
   One delegate responded: ``You couldn't be helping us more. You're
giving us great publicity.''
   Another complained: ``This wouldn't happen in Bavaria,'' the
nation's conservative stronghold.
   The German National Democratic Party's platform calls for
expelling foreigners as a way to maintain a ``national German
identity.''
   The rally came two days after the West German government outlawed
a neo-Nazi party and two weeks after ultra-right candidates were
elected to the West Berlin Parliament.
   The democratic party has about 6,000 members, according to West
German Interior Ministry figures.
   City officials had banned the rally, saying they feared violence.
   Rahden has a population of about 12,000 and is 37 miles south of
the northern port city of Bremen.
   A regional court Friday struck down the ban and an appeals court
upheld that ruling.
</TEXT>
