<SECOND>AM-Obit-Short Man,0144</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Shortest Man Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Antonio Ferreira, who for a time was
listed as the world's shortest man, died of a respiratory illness at
the age of 44, the LUSA news agency reported Saturday.
   Ferreira, who was 29 inches tall, died Friday, according to LUSA.
As a drummer with a musical group, The Pop Kings, Ferreira had
toured South Africa and Japan.
   Ferreira was succeeded as the world's shortest known human adult
by Nelson de la Rosa, of the Dominican Republic. According to the
Guinness Book of World Records, he measures 28.3 inches tall.
   Dozens of friends and family attended Ferreira's funeral in his
home village of Arcozelo in northern Portugal on Saturday.
   Village priest Jose Branco paid tribute to Ferreira, saying ``men
are not measured by their size, but by the deeds they do.''
</TEXT>
