<FIRST>r a AM-WellesAuction     02-11 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Welles Auction,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fans, Curious Buy Memorabilia Of Orson Welles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>POMPANO BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fans of Orson Welles and the curious
lined up to pay $180 for a postcard with his picture and signature
on it and $3,500 a sculpture that once belonged to the late
actor-director.
   ``I'm going to get something,'' said Ellen Hart, 70, who cowered
in a Pennsylvania farmhouse in 1938 as the ``aliens'' in Welles'
frighteningly realistic radio play ``War of the Worlds'' drew
closer. ``I want a piece of a man who gave us so many memories.''
   More than 550 items from Welles' Hollywood estate went on the
block at a three-day auction that began Friday at C.B. Charles
Auction Galleries.
   ``Orson Welles liked to surround himself with the finest of
everything,'' said owner C.B. Charles, who purchased the items last
year from a longtime girlfriend of Welles for an undisclosed sum.
   ``There was only one Orson Welles, and people are still
fascinated by him,'' said Charles.
   Welles died Oct. 10, 1985, in Hollywood of a heart attack after a
long bout with diabetes.
   On Friday, a standing-room-only audience of more than 300 bid an
autographed publicity photograph of Welles in the classic 1941 film
``Citizen Kane'' to $110. A book with a self-portrait caricature on
the front page was snatched for $225, while a 17{-inch bronze
sculpture of a Russian soldier on horseback sold for $3,500.
   A working pocket watch went for $260; a broken one went for $140;
a French postcard with Welles' face on it, signed by Welles himself,
went for $180.
   ``We really came here just for a glimpse of what Welles was like
as a man,'' said Tom Black of Miami. ``Looking at what people own is
such an insight into what they were really like.''
   Welles directed or acted in more than 60 films and won an Oscar
for screenwriting for ``Citizen Kane,'' loosely based on the life of
newspaper tycoon William Randolph Hearst.
   Susan Grimes' parents were children when Welles fooled the nation
with ``War of the Worlds,'' but the mystique of the event was still
strong for her.
   ``It's part of American lore,'' said Grimes, 34. ``It will be a
long time before we forget Orson Welles.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
