<FIRST>r w AM-CruiseSafety 1stLd-Writethru a0564 02-11 0501</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cruise Safety, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0564,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coast Guard Moving to Tighten Small Boat Safety Rules</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf pvs, bgng: ``Written after...'' to CORRECT spelling
of `Cummins'; picks up 3rd graf pvs, bgng: ``The boats...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The proliferation of harbor dinner cruises,
overnight fishing trips, whale-watching excursions, ``booze
cruises'' and commuter ferries _ coupled with a series of accidents
_ has led the Coast Guard to propose new safety standards for small
passenger vessels.
   Written after a 1951 charter boat collision off Long Island left
56 dead, the small passenger safety law has remained largely
unchanged since 1963 while a multitude of new uses has sprung up,
says Coast Guard Cmdr. William Cummins.
   The boats, defined as carrying more than six passengers and
displacing less than 100 gross tons, used to be predominately for
day fishing trips and small ferry boats.
   Most of today's vessels are much bigger than the boats of the
1950s and 1960s and often are carry hundreds _ and in several cases
thousands _ of passengers, Cummins said.
   Uses include high-speed passenger ferries, harbor taxies, dinner
cruises, whale-watching and other tour boats, the popular ``booze
cruise'' floating parties and chartered fishing trips that extend
for days at a time.
   Ocean liners, large ferry boats and other vessels more than 100
gross tons fall under separate rules and already face tougher safety
standards.
   Proposed new requirements include improved life-saving equipment,
radar and electronic position-fixing equipment for certain new
vessels as well as public address systems for all new vessels and
existing vessels with more than one passenger deck.
   Emergency lighting on vessels more than 65 feet, fire
extinguishing systems for enclosed machinery spaces, fire pumps
capable of remote operation, smoke detectors on certain vessels,
passenger manifests and mandatory public safety announcements are
also on the list.
   In addition, wooden boats or vessels operating in salt water
would have to go into drydock every two years for repairs and
inspection.
   The National Transportation Safety Board has long pushed for an
overhaul of the small passenger vessel regulations.
   Michael Benson, an NTSB spokesman, said the Coast Guard's
proposed rules ``certainly go in the right direction.''
   ``The board has felt and recommended for some time that the
changes are needed because the old rules are inadequate,'' he said.
``Whether the new rules go as far as the board would like we'll only
know after an evaluation, which has just begun.''
   Industry representatives said they too are still analyzing the
proposals and their potential impact.
   ``As businessmen they're pro-safety, but I don't think they've
been able to assess what the government regulations will mean to
them individually,'' said Peter Lauridsen, a technical consultant
for the National Association of Passenger Vessel Owners.
   The proposals would cost the industry about $8.5 million a year,
the Coast Guard estimate. Released Jan. 30, they are subject to 120
days of public comments. Cumins said he does not expect the final
rules to be adopted until mid-1990.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
