<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     02-11 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Very Light Snow Around Great Lakes, West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Light snow was widely scattered Saturday with little significant
accumulation.
   Snow showers and squalls spread flakes during the afternoon over
northern New York state, northern Maine and Michigan.
   Advisories for snow squalls were posted over north-central New
York state, near Lake Ontario.
   Snow also was scattered from eastern Idaho across Utah and
western Colorado, as well as from east-central across west-central
Nevada.
   The heaviest snowfall during the 6 hours up to 1 p.m. EST was 1
inch at Sault Ste. Marie, Mich., and Mount Washington, N.H.
   Elsewhere, light rain fell over southern Texas.
   Around the nation at 3 p.m. EST, temperatures ranged from 5
degrees at Helena, Mont., to 79 at Miami. Saturday's official
overnight low was 5 below zero at Helena.
   For Sunday, showers were forecast from northeastern Texas across
Arkansas, northern Louisiana, central Mississippi and central
Alabama. Snow was forecast from northern New England across northern
and western New York state, over Upper Michigan, and from eastern
Nevada across Utah.
   Highs in the 20s and 30s were predicted over most of the northern
Plains, the upper Missouri Valley, the Rockies, the Great Basin of
Nevada and western Utah, the upper Mississippi Valley, the Great
Lakes, the northern Appalachians, and from New England across New
Jersey; in the 30s and 40s over the Ohio Valley; in the 40s in part
of the northern Plains from southern Montana across western South
Dakota; in the 40s and 50s from Maryland and Delaware across the
Virginias, North Carolina, the Tennessee Valley, the central
Mississippi Valley, from Kansas across northern Texas, and the
northern two-thirds of the Pacific Coast; and in the 60s and 70s
over the remainder of the nation.
</TEXT>
