<FIRST>u w AM-SalvadorRebel 1stLd-Writethru a0540 02-11 0626</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador Rebel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0540,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>For Release at 6:30 p.m. EST. Time set by source</HEAD>
<HEAD>Insurgent Says He Supports ``Democratic'' System</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBS 15th graf, bgng, `There was,' to CORRECT Abrams' title
to former assistant secretary of state for inter-American affairs.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of Salvador's leftist rebel movement
says in an article released Saturday his group is far more moderate
than is widely believed and seeks a new system that is ``open,
flexible, pluralistic and democratic.''
   Joaquin Villalobos, commander of the Farabundo Marti National
Liberation Front, said the revolutionary government he is fighting
for ``should avoid confrontation with the United States'' because El
Salvador's ties to it are stronger than those his country has
elsewhere.
   Villalobos outlined his views in an article in Foreign Policy
magazine, which described it as his first comprehensive statement
for an English-language publication.
   The Reagan administration spent an average of well over $100
million a year in military aid to El Salvador to prevent a takeover
of that country by Villalobos and his followers, seeing them as
intent on establishing a Marxist state with strong ties to Cuba and
the Soviet Union.
   The prevailing view in administration has been that the
Salvadoran rebels are far more radical than the insurgency in
Nicaragua which seized power nine years ago.
   But Villalobos wrote that ``it is neither possible nor
necessary'' in El Salvador to ``eliminate totally'' the private
sector, establish a single-party system, bar other parties from the
media, break with the church or eliminate elections.
   ``The FMLN,'' he said, ``pursues an El Salvador that is open,
flexible, pluralistic and democratic in both the economic and
political spheres.''
   With presidential elections set for next month, El Salvador is
entering a crucial stage. The FMLN recently moved away from its
support of a peaceful settlement based on power sharing to one of
support, under certain conditions, for the existing electoral
process.
   Although no agreement has been reached with the govenrment,
Villalobos called the proposal ``a final effort to avoid a social
explosion.''
   Rejecting the Cuban model, which emphasizes total state control
over the economy, Villalobos said a ``combination of the private and
public sectors can lead to more rapid development of Salvadoran
society than a supposedly more radical and closed model.''
   Further emphasizing his preference for pragmatic policies,
Villalobos said ``an ideological approach is of no use if it does
not resolve the problems of poverty. But El Salvador cannot develop
if the United States does not understand its situation and drives it
to develop a war economy.''
   He also called for freedom of expression.
   ``Through debate and education, the masses can learn why they
should defend their historic achievement, the revolution itself,''
he said. ``But this knowledge cannot be developed without
opposition, without an understanding of the opposition's point of
view.''
   He added that to promote debate, ``professional journalism that
is both independent and critical is fundamental.''
   There was no immediate comment by the State Department on
Villalobos' article but shortly before returning to private life
last month, Elliott Abrams, former assistant secretary of state for
inter-American affairs, said he expected that the Salvadoran rebels
would expand efforts to influence public opinion in the United
States.
   He said the Sandinista government in Nicaragua was able to
influence Congress last year to suspend aid to the Contra rebels and
he predicted a similar attempt by the FMLN to persuade the lawmakers
to reduce aid to the Salvadoran government.
   A recent State Department report said there has been a steady
increase in FMLN ``assassinations, kidnapings, use of
pressure-detonated mines that kill and maim indiscriminately.''
   It said that guerrilla mines killed 39 people and injured more
than 130 in the first nine months of 1988.
</TEXT>
