<FIRST>r a AM-MistakenMurder     02-11 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mistaken Murder,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Men Convicted In Slaying Of Teen-Ager Suspected Wrongly Of Rape</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men have been convicted in the 1987
slaying of a teen-ager who they mistakenly accused of raping the
80-year-old grandmother of one of the men.
   A Tarrant County jury deliberated less than 40 minutes Friday
before convicting Norris Wayne Hicks and Boyd Ballard of murder in
the Nov. 27, 1987, shooting of Jeffery Donnelle, who died eight days
later.
   ``It's a shame, because he (Donnelle) wasn't guilty,'' said Terri
Moore in closing arguments. ``This 17-year-old kid absolutely died
for nothing.''
   After Donnelle's death, police determined his blood type did not
match the blood type of the person who raped the elderly woman. No
one has been charged in the rape.
   The jury will return Monday to set punishment for Hicks, 36, of
nearby Arlington, and Ballard, 35, of Alabama. They face sentences
of five to 99 years or life in prison.
   During the three-day trial, witnesses testified that Donnelle was
killed because the two defendants were under the impression that
Donnelle had raped Ballard's grandmother.
   A stepdaughter of Hicks testified that the 80-year-old woman had
identified Donnelle as her attacker from a television news report
and a photograph.
   Defense attorneys argued unsuccessfully that prosecution
witnesses were doing the same thing that the two men had done _
mistakenly identifying them as killers.
   Hicks' wife, Ruby Nell Gay Hicks, faces a charge of conspiracy to
commit murder in connection with the same case.
</TEXT>
