<FIRST>r i AM-Salvador     02-11 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peasants March In Capital To Support Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 12,000 peasants and farm
workers marched through the capital on Saturday to defend the
Christian Democratic government's land reform program.
   The peaceful rally was staged by the pro-government National
Union of Farmworkers.
   The group has warned against erosion of the gains made during the
9-year-old land reform program, which redistributed nearly a third
of the tiny Central American nation's arable land.
   Presidential elections are scheduled March 19 and the rightist
Republican Nationalist Alliance is favored to win.
   Some Christian Democrats and leftists fear the rightists may try
to overturn the land reform program, though the Republican National
Alliance denies such intentions.
   Also Saturday, about 1,000 people in the eastern provincial
capital of San Miguel marched in support of the mayor, who like his
counterparts has been threatened with death by leftist guerrillas
fighting the U.S.-backed government.
   The mayor, Ricardo Leon, said he would not resign as have 90 of
the country's 262 mayors.
   The Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, the guerrilla
army, since early 1988 has waged an intimidation campaign against
municipal authorities. The rebels have assassinated nine mayors.
   The insurgents accuse municipal authorities of helping to
implement what they call ``the U.S.-imposed counterinsurgency
project.''
   The resignation of more than a third of the country's mayors has
created administrative problems. A substitute, usually from the
municipal council, carries out some mayoral functions in most cases,
but some towns have been left virtually without municipal authority.
</TEXT>
