<FILEID>AP-NR-02-11-89 1803EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Nicaragua     02-11 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua,0414</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ortega: Bush Should Heed Central American Presidents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega on Saturday
urged President Bush to abide by whatever decisions the Central
American presidents reach during their upcoming summit.
   Ortega told a news conference that the summit that begins Monday
will help revive the dormant Central American peace plan.
   ``We can assert that the plan is not dead ... but instead that it
is being strengthened by the will of the Central American
presidents,'' Ortega told a news conference.
   ``I hope President Bush respects the decisions that we Central
American presidents reach'' at the summit, he said.
   The summit of the presidents of Honduras, Nicaragua, Guatemala,
Costa Rica and El Salvador is to be held in El Salvador.
   Ortega said he will propose:
   _ A plan under which Central America and the United States can
jointly fight the illegal drug trade. ``Drugs are produced by the
south, consumed by the north, and in their transit they go through
Central America,'' Ortega said.
   _ Suggest having international observers ``from the United
Nations, the Organization of American States ... and other
countries'' to oversee elections.
   _ Discuss regional economic subjects. ``The Central American
region demands economic backing without discrimination of any sort.''
   _ Pursue a proposal he has given Honduran President Jose Azcona
Hoyo to repatriate Nicaraguan Contra rebels and their relatives who
are in Honduras. ``This effort could be supported by the U.S.
Congress.''
   The summit was supposed to take place in August and had been
postponed at least five times. The leaders are to meet under a plan
they signed in August 1987 designed to bring peace to Central
America.
   Congress last February stopped military aid to the Contras, who a
month later signed a preliminary cease-fire with the Sandinista
government. The Sandinistas have been extending the truce month by
month and now only sporadic violations occur.
   Asked about reports that Contra leaders would be at the summit
and would try to meet with the Nicaraguan delegation, Ortega said
the Contras ``have no place'' at a meeting of Central American
presidents.
   Ortega added that ``the possibility exists'' that U.S.-Nicaraguan
relations can return to normal. The United States, which had been
aiding the Contras since 1981, imposed a trade embargo on Nicaragua
in 1985.
   Nicaragua is suffering from a serious economic crisis with
rampant inflation and low productivity.
</TEXT>
