<HEAD>Working Group on Legal Reform Starts Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legal experts from the government and the
opposition began working together Saturday on ways to reform
Poland's judicial system.
   Representatives of the banned trade union Solidarity plan to
raise the issue of the need for a more independent judiciary, said
historian Bronislaw Geremek, an opposition figure.
   The talks are part of the historic negotiation session that began
Monday between the government and the opposition, led by Solidarity
leader Lech Walesa.
   The talks are aimed at reforming the political, social and
economic framework of the country. Small groups have been set up to
address individual issues.
   The full negotiations are expected to last four to six weeks.
   Meanwhile, a strike over pay by transport workers in Piotrkow
Trybunalski, a central Polish provincial city of 80,000 people,
continued Saturday, Polish television said. The strike began Friday
and is backed by the official trade union OPZZ.
   Strikes for higher pay that began Friday also continued at two
departments in a steel plant in Ostrowiec Swietokrzyski near Kielce
in central Poland and at the Laziska steel mill in southern Poland,
the state-run news agency PAP said Saturday.
   The OPZZ was leading the strike at Ostrowiec Swietokrzyski, state
media reported Friday. A Solidarity spokeswoman said Saturday that
striking workers at the Laziska steel mill said their action was
spontaneous and not led by any union.
