<FIRST>r a AM-ShipCollision 1stLd-Writethru a0610 02-11 0568</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ship Collision, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0610,0579</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Missing After Cruise Ship Slices Cuban Freighter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 16th graf, `A crew...', with ship leaving port.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The captain of a luxury liner that sliced a disabled
Cuban freighter in two said Saturday his crew was not at fault in
the pre-dawn collision that left three Cuban crewmen missing.
   The cruise ship Celebration arrived home in Miami on Saturday as
federal transportation officials, the Coast Guard and its insurer,
Lloyd's of London, questioned the crew about the Friday morning
collision off Cuba.
   Despite an 18-inch gash and black scrape marks on its bow, the
734-foot cruise ship sustained only minor damage, and none of its
1,500 passengers or 600 crewmembers was injured, a Carnival Cruise
Lines spokesman said.
   Capt. Rafaele Gravino, master of the Celebration, said the
350-foot Cuban vessel, the Capitan San Luis, was drifting without
lights or steering in a major shipping channel and made no effort to
warn his crew of the impending collision.
   ``The fault is with the ship that had no lights,'' said Gravino.
   But the helmsman of the Cuban vessel said Saturday his captain
tried to warn the Celebration and maneuver to avoid the accident,
reported Prensa Latina, Cuba's official news agency.
   ``We signaled the other ship to let us maneuver and tried to
change course to avoid an accident,'' said Ramon Lahera, whose right
leg was amputated after the collision.
   Prensa Latina said Lahera remains hospitalized in Holguin in
eastern Cuba, and the search continues for the captain and two other
lost crewmen.
   Gravino also said his crew was not to be blamed for failing to
check radar for 27 minutes prior to the accident.
   ``When there is no visibility, the radar is checked very
frequently. But when there is good visibility, you are supposed to
see the lights of the other ship,'' Gravino said during a news
conference aboard the ship.
   His crew didn't see the cement hauler until they were 300 feet
apart, he said. His officers threw the engines into reverse, but it
was too late to avoid slamming into the disabled freighter.
   The Cuban crew told their rescuers that the freighter had lost
electrical power. But Carnival spokesman Tim Gallagher said they
still could have warned passing ships of its plight.
   ``When you do not have emergency lights, you can still raise oil
lamps, use the radio or shoot flare guns,'' he said.
   Gravino quickly left the news conference to meet with
investigators from the National Transportation Safety Board, which
has conducted a series of hearings in Miami on cruise line safety.
   NTSB officials said they were looking into the incident even
though it involved a Liberian-registered cruise liner and a Cuban
freighter en route from Havana to the Canary Islands.
   A crew from the Coast Guard's marine safety office judged the
vessel to be seaworthy and it set sail Saturday afternoon on another
weeklong trip to the Caribbean, Gallagher said.
   The Celebration's crew rescued 42 of the 45 Cuban crew members,
the Coast Guard said. The surviving sailors were picked up by a
Cuban navy frigate and tug and 13 were hospitalized in Cuba, Prensa
Latina reported.
   The three missing men included the ship's captain, Manuel Velazco
Morales, 34, Antonio Campos de los Reyes, 41, and Ivan Freyre Diaz,
40, all of Havana, the news agency reported.
</TEXT>
