<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Film     02-11 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Film,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>Film On Solidarity Back In Polish Theater</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The award-winning film ``Man Of Iron,''
which chronicled the birth of the Solidarity trade union movement,
is being shown at a theater here for the first time since its
official premiere in 1981.
   The film, which includes a cameo appearance by Solidarity leader
Lech Walesa, returned to view last week, the same week the
government and the outlawed union began their historic talks on
reforming Poland.
   Directed by Andrezj Wajda, the movie was awarded the Grand Prix
prize at the Cannes International Film Festival in 1981 and
nominated for an Academy Award the same year.
   A product of the cultural explosion during the 1980-81 period in
which the communist government approved Solidarity as the only legal
independent union in the East Bloc, the film disappeared from
theaters after the martial-law crackdown in December 1981.
   ``Man of Iron'' is playing three times daily in the Palace of
Culture and Science, a Stalin-era structure that towers over central
Warsaw.
   ``Man of Iron'' depicts the rise of Solidarity during a strike of
Gdansk shipyard workers led by Walesa.
   It is a sequel to ``Man of Marble,'' which explored the
tribulations of a bricklayer plucked from obscurity to be displayed
as a model worker during the 1950s.
</TEXT>
