<HEAD>Iranian Monarchists Mark Anniversary</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Iran-Anniversary, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranian monarchists marched through central London
on Saturday to demonstrate support for Prince Reza Pahlavi, the son
of the late shah of Iran.
   The march coincided with the 10th anniversary of the Islamic
revolution that overthrew the monarchy.
   The demonstrators, led by a man wearing a mask of the Iranian
leader Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeni, shouted anti-Khomeini slogans as
they marched past Hyde Park.
   Police reported no incidents.
   The demonstrators, estimated by the organizers to number 3,000 to
5,000, said in a statement Iran had been ``taken back into the
Middle Ages, both socially and economically'' by the fundamentalist
revolution, which drove Reza's late father, Shah Mohammad Reza
Pahlavi into exile.
   In Tehran, 3 million to 4 million took to the streets for a rally
celebrating the anniversary, the climax of 10 days of celebrations
that began Feb. 1, the date in 1979 when Khomeini returned to Tehran
in triumph after 15 years in exile.
