<FIRST>r i AM-Uganda-Election     02-11 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Uganda-Election,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ugandans Choose Members of Expanded Legislative Council</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ugandans voted Saturday for members of an
expanded legislative council in an election critics said was aimed
at entrenching the government of President Yoweri Museveni.
   The National Resistance Council, the legislative body of
Museveni's National Resistance Movement, was to be expanded from 98
members, all presidential appointees, to 278.
   Of that number, however, 68 still will be presidential appointees
and the remainder were being selected only indirectly in Saturday's
complicated balloting procedure.
   One of four main political parties in Museveni's coalition
government boycotted the election, saying it was being held ``in
order to hoodwink citizens into keeping (the government) in power.''
   Critics also pointed out that tens of thousands of displaced
people in northern Uganda, the scene of fighting between rebel and
government troops, would be disenfranchised.
   Voters participated at the village level, electing nine members
to a so-called Resistance Council. The councils in each of the 149
counties meet to elect a nine-member executive committee. Members of
each committee elect from among themselves a representative to the
National Resistance Council.
   Museveni, who waged a 5-year brush war against former President
Milton Obote, seized power in February 1986, when his troops forced
from office a group of military officers who had ousted the civilian
president six months earlier.
   Obote led Uganda to independence from Britain in 1962 but was
overthrown by Idi Amin in 1971. Obote regained the presidency after
Imin was overthrown in 1978.
</TEXT>
