<FIRST>r a AM-Thursday'sChild 1stLd-Writethru a0592 02-11 0561</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thursday's Child, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0592,0571</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yacht Targeting Sunday To Beat 135-year New York-San Francisco Record</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf to UPDATE with new location, speed, and wind conditions.
Picks up 6th graf, ``The crew...</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY13</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The yacht Thursday's Child, zigzagging north
against strong headwinds, should arrive in San Francisco Bay on
Sunday to beat by eight days the New York-San Francisco speed record
set 135 years ago, a spokeswoman said Saturday.
   ``It will be the early morning,'' said Sylvia Wilkerson, a
shore-based spokeswoman for the three-man crew. ``They just want to
get in.''
   Since Nov. 23, the 10-ton racing yacht has logged some 15,000
miles in a voyage around dreaded Cape Horn off the tip of South
America. The period included a stop at the Falkland Islands to make
repairs after the boat collided with an unknown object.
   In the past seven years, five other racing boats have been sunk
rounding Cape Horn in futile attempts to beat the record set by the
clipper ship Flying Cloud in 1854 _ New York to San Francisco in 89
days, eight hours.
   Saturday afternoon, an airplane with an Associated Press reporter
and photographer aboard spotted Thursday's Child about 10 miles
southwest of Santa Cruz and 75 miles from the Golden Gate. The yacht
was moving almost due north at 8 to 10 knots in about 15 knots of
wind.
   The crew _ skipper-owner Warren Luhrs, 44, Courtney Hazleton, 32,
and Lars Bergstrom, 54, who helped design the high-tech vessel _
were in for a welcome from hundreds of boats at the finish under the
Golden Gate Bridge.
   The news earlier Saturday was not so good. Shifting winds had
dropped to a slight breeze overnight as the boat struggled to
progress north. At midnight, the boat was making only 7{ knots, less
than 9 mph.
   Although tired from the constant tacking, which requires the crew
to leap from one side of the cockpit to the other to manipulate the
sail as the boat zigzags northward, the crew was well, Wilkerson was.
   Hazleton, talking over the radio one day last week, called the
adventure ``some of the finest sailing I ever had. I would do it
again at the drop of a hat.''
   But it was with awe and respect for the power of the sea that he
recalled the boat's navigation of Cape Horn, which is always torn by
roaring winds.
   `It got pretty bad ... very unpleasant,'' Hazelton said. He said
the vessel spent six days and nights sailing into the teeth of winds
gusting to 60 knots, through seas that raged against the boat from
all directions.
   The clipper Flying Cloud, a merchantman that also ferried Gold
Rush adventurers to San Francisco, could lay on 35 sails on its tall
masts. It was the fastest of thousands of sailing clippers that
raced each other across the Atlantic and Pacific.
   Ironically, the ship's record-setting performance in 1854
coincided with the beginning of the end of this country's sailing
commerce. In that year, U.S. shipbuilders quit clipper construction
because freight rates had dropped and the oak that went into the
ships became too expensive.
   Steam sealed the doom of the clippers. And the rocks off St.
Johns, Newfoundland, did likewise to the Flying Cloud in 1874.
Nothing is left of it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
