<FIRST>u i AM-China-Crash 1stLd-Writethru a0591 02-11 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0591,0445</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pilot Reportedly Asks To See Uncle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pilot of an F-5E jet fighter from Taiwan that
crashed in China has asked authorities to help him find his uncle,
an official report said Sunday.
   The China News Service said Lt. Col. Lin Xianshun, 35, who
parachuted to safety Saturday, was looking for his uncle, Lin Yuyi.
   ``But authorities have yet to find the uncle,'' said an official
at the state-run news agency.
   The official, who would only identify himself as Zhang, said it
was not clear whether the pilot wished to defect to China.
   ``He has only raised this one request _ to see his uncle,'' he
said. ``We are trying to interview him but he is still in the
hospital.''
   Air Force officials in Taiwan said the fighter, which was on a
training flight, lost contact with a radio tower at Chihhang Air
Base, 180 miles southeast of Taipei on Saturday morning.
   The plane went down in a rice paddy in Fengshun County later that
morning, about 180 miles north of Canton, the provincial capital of
Guangdong province, Chinese reports said.
   Chinese reports said the plane crashed because it ran out of oil.
   Canton television reported Lin was taken by helicopter to the
China Air Force Hospital in Canton. A Chinese reporter Saturday
night said Lin was injured slightly on his backside and arm.
   In Taiwan, a relative of the pilot said he believed the officer
defected to China to see his grandmother. But the pilot's wife, Lin
Xuezhen, said she believed her husband had lost his way in bad
weather.
   The relative, who spoke to reporters on condition of anonymity
from Miaoli, 30 miles south of Taipei, said Lin had complained that
military officers were banned from visiting China.
   In 1987, the Nationalist government in Taiwan eased a ban to
allow all Taiwanese, except military personnel and government
employees, to visit China.
   More than a dozen Nationalist Air Force officers have sought
asylum in China since 1949 when the Nationalists fled to Taiwan
after losing a civil war to the Communist forces on the mainland.
   The latest was Li Dawei, who defected in 1983 in a trainer plane.
Li received $40,000 plus use of a chauffeured limousine. China late
last year abolished the system of rewards for Taiwanese military
personnel defecting to the mainland.
   The Taiwan still offers rewards for Chinese military defectors
but they reduced them in September when China stopped its rewards.
   China regards Taiwan as a renegade province and the two are
technically at war.
</TEXT>
