<HEAD>17 Horses Die in Barn Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YELLOW SPRINGS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A barn fire that could be seen six
miles away killed 17 thoroughbred horses Friday, including one that
had $107,000 in race winnings, officials and the owner said.
   Neither the barn nor the horses were insured.
   ``This loss is not in dollars. It is much more than that,'' said
Chester Gayheart, who owned the farm south of Yellow Springs. ``I
really don't know what I will do. It's going to take some time for
me to think.''
   Gayheart said he has raised horses for 30 years. Among the horses
killed was ``Our Lucky Bell,'' a mare that Gayheart said had won
$107,000 in multiple stakes races.
   The fire was discovered by Gayheart's daughter, who saw flames
from her house. Gayheart said she tried to save a prized horse but
was driven back by smoke and heat.
   Xenia Township Fire Chief Cliff Beegle said the blaze was visible
from Xenia, six miles away. The cause is under investigation.
