<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Food     02-11 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Food,0475</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Food Scares Prompt Government Action</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A food-poisoning scare prompted a government
warning Friday to pregnant women against eating soft cheeses, and
farmers were ordered to slaughter salmonella-infected chicken flocks.
   Britain faced food-poisoning scares on three fronts as police
were called in to investigate the mercury contamination of butter
from the country's largest producer.
   Sir Donald Acheson, the government's chief medical officer,
warned pregnant women not to eat soft cheeses such as Camembert and
brie after these were linked to several listeria infections in
Britain and abroad.
   The bacteria could cause miscarriages and stillbirths, he said.
   The Lancet, a British medical journal, reported last week that
two women infected with listeria suffered spontaneous abortions at a
British hospital, while two other listeria-infected women had to
have Caesarian operations to save their babies.
   Acheson said Camembert was safe to eat for everyone except
pregnant women. ``As far as listeria is concerned, the risk is so
small that it is quite appropriate for the rest of the public to
carry on as before.''
   Press Association, the domestic news agency, said the government
planned to set up a committee to examine all aspects of food
poisoning.
   Acheson listed several other measures the public should take to
avoid food poisoning. His remarks, at a news conference, reflected
heightened public alarm over food poisoning, which began in December
with a salmonella-in-eggs scare.
   Egg sales fell 60 percent after a junior health minister, Edwina
Currie, said most British egg production was infected with
salmonella.
   Confronted by lawsuits from angry farmers, Mrs. Currie resigned,
but the affair has prompted a major debate.
   Also on Friday, the Agriculture Department announced that chicken
flocks contaminated by salmonella would be slaughtered and their
owners compensated.
   It said new compulsory monitoring of Britain's 45,000 flocks had
been introduced. Compensation will be paid according to the bird's
value immediately before slaughter, said a spokesman, who requested
anonymity.
   It said the volume of compensation, and the number of birds
likely to be slaughtered, were not yet known.
   Egg producers and the National Farmers' Union welcomed the
announcement, and the opposition Labor Party said it showed that
``the government was at last waking up to the problem.''
   Detectives were called to a creamery belonging to Dairy Crest,
Britain's biggest dairy chain, in Camborne, in southwest England,
after mercury was found in a tub of butter at a central England
supermarket.
   Peter Reay, the detective leading the inquiry, said: ``At this
stage there is no evidence to suggest that contamination of the
product is widespread.''
   The plant where the contaminated butter was made is to close with
the loss of 118 jobs, but company spokesman John Friend said he
doubted the mercury was planted by a disgruntled worker.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
