<FIRST>r a AM-HarvardDoctor     02-11 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Harvard Doctor,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Doctor Forced to Resign Over Plagiarism Given New Post</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Harvard professor and hospital director
who resigned his posts amid charges of plagiarism has been rehired
by the hospital, officials said Friday.
   Dr. Shervert H. Frazier, 67, a former director of the National
Institute of Mental Health, was named McLean Hospital's staff
psychiatrist and psychiatrist in chief emeritus, an honorary
position.
   Frazier stepped down as hospital director and psychiatry
professor at Harvard Medical School four months ago after a faculty
committee concluded he had plagiarized portions of four papers
between 1966 and 1975.
   His forced resignation sparked criticism from several leading
psychiatrists, who said Harvard officials had overreacted.
   ``If Sherv Frazier had done something like fudge numbers that
killed people, we wouldn't be having this conversation,'' said Dr.
Paul Jay Fink, president of the American Psychiatric Association.
``But when a review article quoted a number of authors and some were
not given full acknowledgement, I'm not sure he should have been so
severely punished.''
   Dr. Lawrence C. Kolb, a New York psychiatrist whose papers were
plagiarized by Frazier, said he was delighted by Frazier's
reappointment at McLean.
   ``I would hope that there would be some kind of a change in the
Harvard position as well,'' he said.
   Dr. Daniel C. Tosteson, dean of the Harvard Medical School, said
in a statement that the reappointment ``expresses appropriate
respect and gratitude for Dr. Frazier's many years of service as an
administrator and a physician concerned for the care of the mentally
ill.''
   But a spokeswoman for the medical school said Harvard has no
plans to restore Frazier's professorship.
   Telephone calls to Frazier's office were not returned Friday and
McLean spokeswoman Sandra Judd said the professor would have no
comment.
</TEXT>
