<FIRST>r i AM-Mexico-StockScandal     02-11 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Stock Scandal,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>All But One Brokerage Firm Under Investigation, Official Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government is investigating reports of
illegal trading by all but one of Mexico's 25 stock brokerage houses
in connection with the 1987 market crash, an official was quoted as
saying Friday.
   Roberto Hoyo D'Addona, the country's fiscal attorney general, was
quoted as saying his department has received 50 complaints of
alleged stockbreaker fraud stemming from the crash.
   Investigations in five of those complaints turned up no evidence
of wrongdoing, he was quoted as saying by Mexico City newspapers.
   He said investigations by the Department of Treasury were being
carried out ``without regard to the political or economic power of
those involved.''
   ``There exist accusations against all of the brokerage firms
except one. The Treasury Department is only investigating if the
National Securities Law has been violated in order to tell the
(attorney general) whether or not crimes exist to prosecute,''
D'Addona said.
   He did not identify possible securities violations but said the
investigations were related to the October 1987 crash, when Mexico's
market index plunged by 74 percent in 28 trading days.
   The Treasury Department is to complete its investigations within
weeks, D'Addona said.
   Attorney General Enrique Alvarez del Castillo said his department
would begin legal proceedings when asked to do so by the Treasury
Department or the National Securities Commission.
   ``These are the instructions of the president,'' he said in
remarks published Friday.
   A congressional panel on Wednesday voted to call D'Addona, Deputy
Attorney General Luis Porte Petit and Oscar Espinosa Villareal,
president of the securities commission, to testify about the fraud
allegations.
   The request went to the Chamber of Deputies' Treasury Committee.
Hearings are expected to begin next week.
</TEXT>
