<FIRST>r i AM-Salvador-Elections 1stLd-Writethru   02-11 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador-Elections, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0813,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parties Willing to Talk to Rebels</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS five grafs at end with rebels meeting with Arias</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's political parties
on Friday agreed to talk with a delegation of guerrilla commanders
about a rebel proposal to participate in this year's presidential
election.
   The 13 political parties, however, did not agree to the rebel
demand that the elections be postponed from March 19 to September.
   The guerrillas' proposal to participate in the elections was made
on Jan. 24. Their demand that the balloting be delayed was strongly
opposed by President Jose Napoleon Duarte and the armed forces.
   Aronette Diaz, leader of the leftist Democratic Nationalist
Union, told a news conference that the political parties agreed that
the guerrilla proposal contains positive elements but that ``doubts
and questions'' about the offer would be expressed to guerrilla
leaders.
   Mrs. Diaz said the parties agreed to send their questions about
the proposal to the guerrillas on Monday. Three days after the rebel
response is received, she said, the parties will invite a delegation
of commanders ``to hold direct conversations in a mutually agreed
upon place.''
   Two guerrilla commanders had offered Thursday to travel to San
Salvador to initiate face-to-face talks on the proposal with party
and government representatives.
   The guerrilla offer to participate in elections was a drastic
shift. The Marxist-led rebels waging a 9-year-old war against the
U.S.-backed government have boycotted the five national elections
held this decade.
   The rebels contend elections are part of a U.S.-imposed
counterinsurgency project to put a civilian facade on a
military-dominated government.
   Meanwhile, in Costa Rica, two Salvadoran rebel commanders met
with Costa Rican President Oscar Arias to seek his support on their
proposal when he meets with fellow Central American leaders
beginning on Monday.
   Jose Mario Lopez and Mercedes del Carmen Letona told a news
conference in the Costa Rican capital of San Jose that they also
sent letters to presidents Vinicio Cerezo of Guatemala and Jose
Azcona Hoyos de Honduras, seeking their support for the proposal.
   Arias, Cerezo, Azcona and Duarte, along with Nicaraguan President
Daniel Ortega, are scheduled to meet in El Salvador Monday and
Tuesday.
   The presidents are to discuss a stalled peace plan they signed in
Guatemala in 1987 which calls for political amnesties and an end to
civil wars in the region.
   The foreign ministers of the five nations on Wednesday asked the
United Nations to send a multinational force of inspectors to
Central America to verify that no country supports subversion
against their neighbors.
</TEXT>
