<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines-Cannibalism     02-11 0444</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-Cannibalism,0456</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Picked In Navy Captain's Court-Martial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIGUEL C. SUAREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SUBIC BAY NAVAL BASE, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury was selected
Friday for the court-martial of a U.S. Navy captain charged with
failing to rescue more than 80 Vietnamese boat people who later
resorted to cannibalism to survive.
   The first witnesses against Capt. Alexander G. Balian are to
testify on Monday.
   Balian, 48, of Los Angeles, is accused of violating lawful orders
and dereliction of duty after his vessel, the USS Dubuque, allegedly
refused to help a boatload of Vietnamese refugees in the South China
Sea on June 9.
   Navy officials said 110 Vietnamese sailed from their homeland,
and that at least 83 men, women and children were still alive when
their vessel met the Dubuque.
   United Nations and Navy officials said 31 of the Vietnamese died
after encountering the Dubuque about 210 miles north of the
Philippine island of Palawan.
   Survivors said two died of starvation and three others were
murdered and eaten by fellow passengers before Filipino fishermen
rescued the Vietnamese on June 27 after 37 days at sea.
   Balian, who won a Silver Star and a Purple Heart in the Vietnam
War, could face 4{ years in prison and a dishonorable discharge if
convicted on all counts, officials said. Four of the six jurors must
agree on a conviction.
   Balian has been charged with failing to rescue an unknown
Vietnamese who swam toward the Dubuque at risk to his life; failing
to rescue a second Vietnamese who tried to climb the warship's ropes
but was shaken off; and failing to render assistance to refugees
``in life-endangering circumstances.''
   He told investigators the Vietnamese boat was seaworthy and that
his crew provided it with food, water and navigational directions.
   During Friday's proceedings, defense lawyer Dan Donato, a retired
Navy captain, asked each of the jurors whether they knew enough
about the case to have formed an opinion. Each indicated he had not.
Donato then told them that if a vote were taken now, ``you're
supposed to vote not guilty.''
   Two prospective jurors, both captains, were dismissed on
challenges by both the prosecution and defense. The eight
prospective jurors, including six U.S. Navy captains, were brought
here from U.S. installations in South Korea, Japan and California.
   Navy officials said the Dubuque, an amphibious landing ship, was
en route to the Persian Gulf to assist U.S. minesweepers when it
crossed paths with the Vietnamese ship about 230 miles north of
Palawan.
   The Vietnamese reported the encounter with the U.S. ship after
reaching a U.N. refugee camp on Palawan, and Balian was relieved
temporarily of his command on Aug. 13.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
