<DOCNO> AP890211-0168 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-11-89 0450EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-KidsMagazine Adv13   02-11 0824</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Kids Magazine, Adv 13,0854</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday AMs, Feb. 13</HEAD>
<HEAD>Sports Illustrated Launches Sports Magazine for Kids</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Don't look for a sexy swimsuit issue from the
latest offspring of Sport Illustrated.
   Sports Illustrated for Kids is aimed at the 8-to-13-year-old
crowd, and publisher Ann S. Moore promises the only people the
magazine will show in bathing suits will be competing in sports like
swimming, water skiing or surfing or else will likely have ``an
Olympic gold medal around their neck.''
   The magazine was launched in January after Mrs. Moore secured
quarter-million dollar commitments from 30 advertisers. Half the
500,000 circulation is sold by subscription or, starting with the
March issue, at newstands.
   The other 250,000 copies are given free to third- through
sixth-graders in 1,000 of the poorest schools in the nation.
   They include places like Carter Elementary School on Chicago's
South Side, where the head of the reading resources program, Jessie
Hamlet, says few students could afford a magazine subscription.
   ``My teachers have been so grateful to have them,'' she said.
``The kids love it. They say things like, `You mean it's ours to
keep?'''
   She hopes the magazine will encourage students to read.
   ``It's something current and the look of it is so nice that it
makes them want to pick it up and read it. That's half the battle
there,'' she said.
   Those are reassuring words to Moore, who says she worked more
than 18 months on developing and launching the magazine.
   Improving literacy was one of the pitches she used in persuading
companies such as IBM and AT&amp;T, as well as sneaker and snack makers,
to pay $250,000 each for a year's worth of advertising space.
   But the motivation isn't entirely altruistic. The magazine is
expected to make a profit eventually, Mrs. Moore said. She said it
also should produce some readers for ``Big SI,'' as she calls the
magazine that spawned it.
   A year's subscription costs $15.95 and single copies will sell
for $1.75. The free copies come with tips for teachers on how to use
the issue in class.
   Jeanne Mannings, a health and physical education teacher at
Adamsville Elementary School in Atlanta, said, ``I set aside one day
a month to go through each article with them to practice their
reading skills.''
   For advertisers, the magazine is supposed to offer an appealing
new avenue to youngsters who are often hard to reach with print ads.
   Mrs. Moore estimates there are 16 million youngsters in the
magazine's target audience, and said they spend $5 billion a year of
their own money and influence another $40 billion spent by their
parents.
   But at $25,000 a page and a guaranteed circulation of 500,000,
the advertisers are paying a premium over other magazines aimed at
children.
   Boys' Life magazine, for instance, charges $17,650 for a page and
has a monthly circulation of 1.3 million. Scholastic Inc. charges
$10,000 for a page in Junior Scholastic magazine with a bimonthly
circulation of 700,000.
   Mrs. Moore said she tried to avoid making her magazine something
that youngsters ``perceive to be good for them.''
   The January issue profiled basketball's Michael Jordan,
football's Doug Williams, sled racer Susan Butcher and described the
ride two 10-year-olds took in a blimp. Each issue has regular
sections explaining rules of the game, advice from the pros, a
celebrity's description of his or her worst day, a poster of an
athlete, training tips, sports quizzes and trading cards.
   Some advertisers developed unique approaches.
   Foot Locker's ads ask who was first to achieve athletic feats,
such as who first shattered a basketball backboard. Converse shoe
ads address questions children have directed to athletes such as
football's Bernie Kosar.
   American Airlines' ads trace the history of flying machines.
   Mary O'Neill, an American spokeswoman, said the carrier wants to
impress on children that American is a quality company. ``When they
start thinking about careers, we hope they think American Airlines
might be a real good place for them to work,'' she said.
   Publisher Moore makes no apologies for sending a magazine with
paid ads into the school rooms. ``We have researched this with
teachers and parents and they welcomed the idea of having a real
magazine with ads,'' she said.
   Some types of ads such as cigarettes or liquor are prohibited and
she hopes to keep the proportion of ads to editorial copy low.
   Teachers said advertising is a small price to pay for the
benefits of getting a quality magazine free.
   A school official in Oakland, Calif., who asked not to be
identified by name, said her teachers have used the magazine to
teach students how advertising works.
   In Chicago, Ms. Hamlet said she has heard no complaints about the
ads.
   ``Wouldn't that be nice (if the magazine carried no ads) but the
real world isn't like that,'' she said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon. AMs, Feb 13</NOTE>
</DOC>
