<SECOND>PM-Markets Rdp,0585</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks, Bonds Fall, Dollar Rises on Inflation Data</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: For Saturday PMs.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Worries about rising inflation and interest rates
sparked the biggest stock selloff of the year, depressed bond prices
and boosted the dollar's value in foreign exchange.
   The Dow Jones industrial average tumbled 36.97 points to 2,286.07
on Friday, the biggest drop in that key market indicator since Nov.
16.
   An accompanying decline in the bond market was more modest but it
extended the losses bonds suffered in a Thursday selloff, which was
the sharpest in three months for the credit markets.
   Meanwhile, the dollar rallied on the prospect that the Federal
Reserve might tighten its monetary policy _ pushing interest rates
even higher _ in an effort to choke off inflation.
   Separately, the nation's biggest banks boosted their prime
lending rates by a half percentage point to 11 percent, the highest
level since late 1984 and a reflection of recent rises in other
rates.
   Roiling the financial markets was the Labor Department's report
Friday morning that wholesale prices jumped 1 percent in January.
   The increase was about twice as large as expected.
   Bond prices tumbled and interest rates surged higher within
moments of the report.
   ``In the first couple of minutes, there was absolute shock,''
said Elliott Platt, fixed-income research director for the
investment firm Donaldson Lufkin &amp; Jenrette Securities. ``The market
went down hard.''
   Prices of the Treasury's 30-year bond, considered a sensitive
gauge of interest rate speculation, fell $10 for every $1,000 in
face value during a burst of trading after the report. Prices edged
back up later in the day in more subdued activity.
   By late trading, prices of the benchmark 30-year bond were down
about $5 for every $1,000 in face value and the yield jumped to 9.03
percent from 8.89 percent late Thursday.
   That loss came on top of Thursday's setback that saw the price of
30-year bonds sink $16.25 for every $1,000 in face value.
   On Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average lost 18 points
after the first 30 minutes of trading, recoverted somewhat at midday
but deteriorated in the afternoon to finish with a 36.97-point loss
for the day.
   But the inflation report supported the dollar, which benefits
from speculation that the Fed will tighten credit and boost interest
rates, which make the dollar more attractive to foreign investors.
   By the end of trading in New York, the dollar traded at 1.8695
West German marks, up from 1.8475 late Thursday, and at 128.68
Japanese yen, up from 127.93 late Thursday.
   President Bush's budget message to Congress on Thursday also was
cited for the sour performance in the stock and bond markets, as
traders faulted him for failing to propose more aggressive steps to
trim the federal deficit.
   ``The markets looked at it as a warmed-over version of (former
President) Reagan's budget. Any changes were modest and around the
edges,'' said Gary Schlossberg, senior financial economist for Wells
Fargo Bank in San Francisco.
   Friday's increase put the prime rate at its highest level since
it reached 10.75 percent in late 1984. The last increase, from 10
percent to 10.5 percent, occurred Nov. 28.
   Some analysts said they expect further increases for the prime,
which is a benchmark for setting interest on a variety of consumer
and corporate loans such as adjustable-rate mortgages.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
